<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Economic Growth Rate Tops 3.5 PC This </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia registered a 3.5
percent economic growth rate this year, two percent below the
targeted 5.5 percent due to unfavorable weather conditions,
Finance Minister Ronald Penza said today.
</P>
<P>
he told a news briefing here that annual inflation rate has
been reduced to 20 percent this year against the target of 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year the country achieved a 6.4 percent economic growth
rate while the inflation rate was brought down to 35.
</P>
<P>
Penza said the economic performance of the country this year
has been positive as it has managed a budget surplus of 62.5
billion Kwacha (about 47 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the October 28 abortive coup, investors' confidence
has not been affected, he said, adding that over 100 million
Dollars has been pumped into the country by investors this year.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that 1998 will be a prosperous year for Zambia as
it will experience unprecedented economic growth while
unemployment will drastically be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Penza said all civil servants who are to be retrenched in the
process of implementing the public service reform program (PSRP)
will be paid their packages.
</P>
<P>
The exercise to be conducted over a two-year period will
gobble a total of 116 billion Kwacha (about 87 million Dollars),
he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will put in 20 billion Kwacha for the exercise,
which will start this month, while donors will foot the other 96
billion Kwacha, according to the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
