<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Expansion Not to Break CIS Military System: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The NATO expansion will not
lead to a breakup of the military system of the Commonwealth of
the Independent States (CIS), a high-ranking CIS official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
General Viktor Prudnikov, chief of the CIS headquarters for
coordinating military cooperation, made the remarks at a press
conference in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He said that although some CIS members are being drawn into
NATO, they are still linked with Russia and other former Soviet
republics by a legacy which will not allow them to break away from
the CIS.
</P>
<P>
He noted that military cooperation is broadening among CIS
countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia has reached agreements with Belorussia and Kazakhstan on
the creation of a joint air defense system and is likely to
conclude similar agreements with Armenia, Georgia, Turkmenistan
and Uzbekistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prudnikov said that the main achievement of the CIS
headquarters over the past four years is the virtual complete
termination of local armed conflicts within the CIS territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
