<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Spending Slows in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. consumer spending
slowed slightly in November with spending increase of 0.4 percent
to 5.59 trillion U.S. dollars at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate, the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
This was down from a 0.5 percent gain in the previous month and
also below analysts' predictions of another 0.5 percent increase
in November.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that personal incomes increase
jumped 0.8 percent to a 7.03 trillion dollar rate, up from 6.97
trillion dollars in October, when they advanced 0.6 percent. It
was the biggest increase since a 1 percent gain in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many retailors say that despite rising incomes and widespread
discounting, they are not experiencing the big sales they expected
during what usually is their busiest period of the year.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods, which include big-ticket items such
as computers and electronic items expected to last more than three
years, rose 0.8 percent in November after falling 0.2 percent in
October. But spending on nondurable goods such as food and fuel
and on services both edged up just 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending usually represents two-thirds of the U.S.
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries shot up 43.1 billion dollars after
climbing 27.6 billion dollars in October. Employment and average
weekly hours and hourly earnings all increased.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income or income after taxes picked up by 0.7
percent, a higher increase from 0.5 percent a month earlier and
the largest gain since a 0.9 percent increase in June 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
