<HEADLINE> Four South Asian Countries to Discuss Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Foreign Minister
Abdus Samad Azad said here Wednesday that foreign secretaries of
Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Bhutan will meet next month to
discuss areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the meeting will discuss
cooperation on water resources, electricity, tourism, trade and
investment among the four member countries of the "Growth
Quadrangle."
</P>
<P>
The "Growth Quadrangle" was initiated in December 1996 by the
then foreign minister of Nepal Prakash Chandra Lohani with a view
to developing jointly the eastern Himalayan rivers for rapid
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi foreign minister said that during his three-day
visit in Nepal, he discussed with the Nepalese leaders about the
sub-regional cooperation within the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) and they all were optimistic about
its future.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the above-mentioned four countries, the SAARC
also includes the Maldives, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi guest also said that water in Nepal is very,
very important for the region's economic development in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a hydropower potential of 83 million kw, but so far
less than one percent has been utilized.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Nepal, Azad discussed with the Nepali side
cooperation in water resources development.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to leave here for home Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
