<HEADLINE> Saudi Calls for Security Cooperation with Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has called
for boosting security cooperation with Yemen and expressed desire
to resolve their long-standing border disputes, the Saudi Press
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a message to his Yemeni counterpart Hussain Moh'd Arab
Wednesday, Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz
called for "means of boosting security cooperation," the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
It is the second message on the issue sent by Nayef to Arab in
a week, according to the agency. But it gave no details of the
message.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources in Saudi capital Riyadh were quoted as saying
that the message came within the context of ongoing consultations
between the two countries after a Yemeni patrol allegedly
infiltrated into Saudi Arabia and killed two Saudis and a Yemeni
last month.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that it is in line with Saudi desire to
enhance bilateral security cooperation and resolve the border
disputes according to the memorandum of understanding signed by
the two Arab neighbors in 1995, which outlined the principles of a
solution.
</P>
<P>
Many parts of the 2,000-kilometer border between Saudi Arabia
and Yemen remain undefined, some of which are believed to be
oil-rich.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been making efforts to settle the border
disputes to eliminate the last obstacle to the development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Abdul-Karim
al-Aryani paid a visit to Saudi Arabia last month to discuss ways
of solving the border disputes.
</P>
<P>
He delivered a letter from Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh
to Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz dealing with the efforts to seek
a solution to the territorial disputes and the shooting incident
at the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
