<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Gradually Increase Military Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Russia will gradually increase
its military spending in the next decade, according to a
governmental program governing the reform and transfer of the
defense industry.
</P>
<P>
The program, which will govern the reform and transfer of the
Russian defense industry till 2005, provides that military
spending will account for 3.5 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) between 1998 and 2000 and 3.3 percent for the period
between the year 2000 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
But since the GDP is expected to increase by five percent
during this period, the net military spending will increase
gradually.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the military reform and transfer, Russian Deputy
Prime Minister Yakov Urinson said that by the year 2005, the
number of defense enterprises will be reduced to 600 from the
current 1700.
</P>
<P>
He said that the reform and transfer are designed to meet the
needs of the changed geopolitics and the country's changed demands
for the military forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
