<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golden Gate Bridge Adds Cables on Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Ironworkers on Thursday
began to install a system of double cables to close a gap on
famous Golden Gate Bridge in San francisco after a tragic accident
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the accident, a two-year-old girl plunged 170 feet to
her death through a gap of 9.5 inches between the sidewalk and the
roadway. The girl's father has blamed her death on defective
bridge design and construction.
</P>
<P>
The two-tiered cables will halve the gap which allowed the
girl's body to slip through. Explaining design reasons for the
gap, an engineer said the space was included so that water and
debris can drain off the bridge and to minimize rocking during
high winds. It also was designed as a buffer in the event that a
car slams into the divider separating the sidewalk and the roadway.
</P>
<P>
The engineer said that the gap complied with the state Uniform
Building Code when the designs were completed in the late
1970s. The code, however, was changed to allow only a six-inch gap
between the time when the designs were draw and the time when the
project was completed. Until the accident, he said, nobody had
ever complained about the gap, let alone fallen into it.
</P>
<P>
A state senator has called for an investigation of all state
bridges to see whether other hazards exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
