<HEADLINE> Iran's Freedom Movement Chief Yazdi Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary General of
Iran's Freedom Movement Ebrahim Yazdi was released today after a
10-day imprisonment, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
A judge of the first branch of Tehran's Islamic Revolution
court was quoted as announcing that Yazdi was detained on December
14 on charges of desecrating religious sanctities.
</P>
<P>
"Yazdi was released today upon completion of the necessary
investigation and posting bail pending the final court verdict,"
said the judge.
</P>
<P>
A staff member from Yazdi's office, who declined to mention
name, confirmed his release in a telephone interview with
Xinhua. However, he said that his organization did not understand
why Yazdi was arrested and why he was freed.
</P>
<P>
On December 15, the Freedom Movement issued a statement saying
that Yazdi was summoned by the Islamic Revolution court for
questioning and then put into Tehran's prison of Evin without any
charges. Iran's Judiciary claimed that Yazdi was detained
according to law.
</P>
<P>
The organization was founded in 1961 by Mehdi Bazargan, late
Iranian prime minister of the interim government formed in the
wake of the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Yazdi was elected as secretary general of the
organization in January 1995 after the demise of Bazargan.
</P>
<P>
However, the organization was not granted formal permission to
carry out activities since the government asked political parties
and organizations to register in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
