<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lamp Map Lightens Up Night Roads in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Newly installed lamp maps are
helping people find their way more easily in the labyrinth of
winding streets and roads in this north China port city,
especially at night.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 lamp maps, turned on and off along with the
street lights, have been installed beside bus stops in the busiest
parts of downtown such as the Heping Road and the Nanjing Road.
</P>
<P>
With the location of the bus stop on the street, the names and
directions of surrounding streets, and the route of the given bus
indicated, the maps are providing both locals and people from
outside the city much convenience in the city famous for its
tricky roads and streets, where one usually starts walking
eastward and yet finds oneself at the southern end of the city.
</P>
<P>
Unlike its neighbor Beijing, where the planning of several
feudal dynasties had given the ancient capital a neat chess-board
pattern with straight north-south and east-west streets, Tianjin
is marked by streets winding through different parts of the city
which used to lead to the concessions of different western powers.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin will have a total of 500 lamp maps installed on 50 main
streets and roads next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
