<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Ngilu, Woman Challenger for Kanya's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- One of the first two women
ever to vie for the top seat in Kenya, Charity Ngilu, as many
people believe, stands a real chance in Monday's poll mainly due
to her clarion call for changes.
</P>
<P>
If successful, she would become sub-Saharan Africa's first
elected female president.
</P>
<P>
She said she strongly believes in education and grass-roots
economic development as the main vehicles for social and economic
emancipation.
</P>
<P>
Elimination of corruption, restoration to people's sense of
self-confidence, freedom from political oppression, one president
one term and gender equality are among the high priorities Ngilu
has listed in her post-election program.
</P>
<P>
She is said to be fresh, clean and untainted by scandals and
has far less tribal color than any other opposition presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
"Ngilu is actually talking about changes and development," a
local political analyst explained to Xinhua why he supports the
woman, adding that his point is common among educated people in
urban areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
With the slogan of "A New Beginning" brandished on banners
that bear her symbol of a clock, an energetic 45-year-old Ngilu
is widely seen as a spokeswoman for the generation after that of
President Daniel arap Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
"I want to be very close to the people, easily accessible and
involve people in making their decisions about every facet of
their life," she said in a recent interview with local media.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not looking for power for the sake of it. I want to be
something of a convener, a facilitator of good governance. I want
to bring Kenyans together to harness their resources and
jump-start this stalled country once again," she claimed.
</P>
<P>
The fact that estimated 55 percent Kenyans are women may also
afford her some advantage.
</P>
<P>
"Men have ruled the country for a long time. May women prove
they are better," said a Luo girl living here who said she surely
will cast her ballot in favor of Ngilu.
</P>
<P>
Her campaign team seemed to have mastered the drills of public
appeal, presenting her as a stable family woman, with her husband
Mike Ngilu, an engineer, two of her three children and her aged
mother, all voiced their support for her run.
</P>
<P>
The concern raised by Ngilu applies to most of the vast
Eastern, Coast, North-Eastern and two-thirds of the Rife Valley
Province where Moi started his career, local observers say.
</P>
<P>
Her presence has invigorated the campaign, but many Kenyan men
and women still believe a man should lead the country. Her Kamba
tribe was solidly behind Moi in 1992 and she herself lacks any
experience in all levels of governance.
</P>
<P>
As one of rare rags-to-riches women in the country, Ngilu rose
to her rank from humble beginnings.
</P>
<P>
She came from a family with a poor Christian preacher for a
father and a hard-working mother who gave birth to a total of 13
children. She is the ninth in the line.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that after more than 30 years of independence
the children of Kenya should be living in circumstances
comparable to those I grew up in," she claimed, saying she knows
the misery of being poor from first-hand experience.
</P>
<P>
After having graduated from Alliance Girls High School, she
attended both the Government Secretarial College and the Kenya
Institute of Administration for a secretarial course.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Ngilu became the personal secretary to the former
Central Bank Governor Duncan Ndegwa for three years before moving
to America-based Chase Manhattan Bank's Nairobi branch as an
administrator.
</P>
<P>
She quit employed ranks in 1989 to start running her family
business -- a small bakery and a restaurant in Machakos town
nearby Nairobi. Later, she launched her main business -- a
plastics extrusion factory in Nairobi's industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
Ngilu first walked into politics in 1992 when she was elected
to parliament for the Democratic Party (DP), led by presidential
candidate Mwai Kibaki, in Kitui Central constituency, Eastern
Province.
</P>
<P>
She said she joined the parliamentary race because she then
was dissatisfied with the way the people were being treated by
their representatives.
</P>
<P>
At the time, she already became famous nationwide when the
Kitui administration barred her from leaving her house for a few
days during her campaign.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, she quit Kibaki's DP so as to run on the
Social Democratic Party (SDP) ticket.
</P>
<P>
Now SDP is the only party in which the chairman is not the
presidential candidate. Ngilu is just an ordinary member while
the chairman is Justus Nyang'aya.
</P>
<P>
Her brush with the riot police at the height of the violent
quest for constitutional reforms in the middle of the year will
be remembered by her supporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
