<HEADLINE> Sharp Drop in Maize Yield Predicted in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Farmers Union
(ZFU) forecast a 45 percent decrease in the country's staple food
maize production during the 1997/98 season due to the prolonged
drought, ZFU President Silas Hungwe has said.
</P>
<P>
Hungwe today told the Zimbabwe News Agency if farmers failed
to secure any meaningful rainfall during the course of this week,
most of the maize crop would be a complete write-off.
</P>
<P>
"The crop situation is pathetic in most parts of the country
and there is poor germination in most areas while other farmers
are still replanting their crops," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hungwe said in some areas, no planting had taken place from
November to date.
</P>
<P>
Crops which had reached tussling stage would be affected in
some parts of the country because of the prolonged dry spell, the
ZFU president noted.
</P>
<P>
Hungwe said the ZFU had advised its farmers to plant in stages
because of the forecast of the El-Nino which spells disaster in
the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are advised to reduce their maize planting since the
season was not a promising one in terms of securing good
rainfall, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Cancel Credit Quota System Starting Next Year (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state-owned banks should balance the sources and uses of
their funds, it noted.
</P>
<P>
In line with the money supply target, regulations on
asset-to-liability management and credit policies published by the
PBC and with the availability of funds, the head offices of the
state-owned banks should compile their fund plans on an annual or
quarterly basis and then pass the plans down to their subsidiaries
for implementation, it said.
</P>
<P>
It added that at the same time the head offices should beef up
their efforts to conduct unified dispatch of the bank funds while
the branch and sub-branch banks should improve their management of
loan terms and fund positions.
</P>
<P>
After the abolition of the credit quota system, the central
bank will strive to regulate money supply and maintain the
stability of the national currency and thereby promote economic
growth through a combined use of indirect monetary tools, such as
interest rate, open market operations, reserves for bank deposits,
discount loans, and rediscounting, it said.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the latest reform, the PBC urged the state-owned
commercial banks to improve credit management and their financial
services.
</P>
<P>
Reasonable loan support for enterprises must not be affected
because of the reform while monitoring over the quality of loan
portfolios must not be slackened to avoid an increase in bad
loans, the central bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
