<HEADLINE> S. Leone Leader Promoted to Lt.-Colonel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's military
ruler Johnny Paul Koroma has been promoted to the rank of
Lieutenant-Colonel in the Sierra Leone army.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Department spokesman said the appointment was made
by the Armed Forces Council, which is responsible for promotion
of all personnel in the military, the navy and the police.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's promotion came first from a news broadcast by the
state run radio concerning a million Dollar donation Wednesday to
an Appeal Fund for relatives of victims of bombardment and
shellings by Nigerian Air Force jets and gunners in October.
</P>
<P>
The donation was made by the Gambian Community in Sierra Leone
to Koroma in a ceremony at State House in which Koroma
disclosed his promotion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a radio and TV Christmas message to the people
of Sierra Leone, Koroma invited all Sierra Leonean refugees in
neighboring Guinea, Liberia and Cote d'Ivoire "to return home and
join their families in contributing to the salvation of the
country."
</P>
<P>
He said to facilitate their return, free transportation will
be provided as from December 27 or Saturday "to enable them to
celebrate the new Year with their respective families."
</P>
<P>
Correspondents have cast doubts on whether many refugees will
take advantage of the offer as similar offers had been ignored in
the past.
</P>
<P>
On national security, Koroma said his administration had
"minimize the activities of armed robberies by the application of
very rigid measures to curb banditry and lawlessness."
</P>
<P>
On the international aspect, Koroma said there is no need for
Nigerian soldiers in the west African peace-keeping force known
as ECOMOG to "interfere into the internal affairs of Sierra
Leone."
</P>
<P>
"The main problem for Sierra Leone remains Nigeria and its
leader General Sani Abacha, and their misapplication of the
sanction and embargo on Sierra Leone," the Sierra Leone leader
claimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
