<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Official Praises Coal Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese vice-premier Wu
Bangguo praised the country's coal sector today for its success in
making profits after 13 consecutive years of operation in the red.
</P>
<P>
Wu, also member of the Political Bureau of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee, said this in a letter of
greetings to the ongoing national conference on coal industry.
</P>
<P>
China's state-run coal mines are expected to turn out 200
million yuan (about 24 million US dollars) in profits this year,
reversing the money-losing situation which lasted for 13 years in
a row.
</P>
<P>
The coal mines have found a successful way to help the
state-owned enterprises in the red to rid of their difficulties
during the period of shifting from the planned economy to the
socialist market economy, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
But it is not a story of "becoming a hero overnight", Wu
pointed out. "The growth of the coal industry will still be
hindered by some long-existing problems and new challenges."
</P>
<P>
Measures, including the introduction of modern enterprise
system, co-ordinating production with market demands and
developing businesses in multiple forms will help the coal
industry to get out of difficulties as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
