<HEADLINE> China, Egypt Urge Israel to Keep Peace Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and visiting Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
today called upon Israel to keep its peace commitments to enable
the Mideast peace process move forward.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Qian made the call at a meeting at the presidential
palace here this morning, during which Qian conveyed a message
from Chinese President Jiang Zemin to the Egyptian leader.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the peace process initiated since the Madrid peace
conference is the sole option and that all parties concerned must
strictly implement relevant U.N. resolutions and the principle of
land for peace," Qian told Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Since Madrid, the Arabs and Israel have reached agreements and
made important progress (in peace-making), and those agreements
should be implemented, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The incumbent Israeli government should also stick to the
pledges and commitments made by the previous Labor government,"
said the Chinese top diplomat.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who has visited Israel during his current multi-nation
Mideast tour, said the Israeli people have a strong desire and
most of them hope to follow the path blazed by late Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin (toward peace).
</P>
<P>
Mubarak agreed with Qian. He blamed the peace deadlock on the
Israeli government's hardline policy, and urged Israel to
"honestly materialize the commitments it has made since the Madrid
conference."
</P>
<P>
He warned that "the Israeli policy that often cites its
security concern as an excuse will lead to serious consequences to
all parties, including Israel."
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed Chinese government's deep concern over the
setbacks in Mideast peace, which he said were due to "man-made
obstacles."
</P>
<P>
"Although China does not act as a mediator in the Middle East
peace process, it feels obliged to explain its view points to
concerned parties," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister stressed that "a permanent settlement of
the Mideast problem necessitates the materialization of the
principle of land for peace and the restoration of legitimate
rights of the Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of Sino-Egyptian relations, Egypt's vital role
in both international and regional affairs, as well as the Egypt's
diplomatic policy of independence and non-alignment.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mubarak criticized the practice of interfering in
other countries' domestic affairs on the pretext of protecting
human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt, despite pressure from outside, believes that it has no
such a right to interfere in the internal affairs of other
countries. It also objects to pressuring China under the pretext
of human rights," said the president.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, it is those countries with the worst human rights
record that usually apply pressure on other countries over the
human rights issue," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Qian voiced Chinese government's appreciation of Cairo's stance
in this regard. He extended an invitation from President Jiang
Zemin for Mubarak to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the last leg of Qian's ongoing Middle East tour which
has taken him to Lebanon, Syria, Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas since December 18.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here Wednesday, has held talks with his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
