<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Calls for Measures to Prevent Financial Risks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"China's overall financial order is good but some financial
risks have begun to crop up," the article by Wang Yu said.
</P>
<P>
China has scored world-acknowledged achievements in
reforming and opening its financial sector in recent years, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The achievements have played a significant role in
enhancing and improving macro-economic control, controlling
inflation, promoting economic growth and maintaining social
stability, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
However, some financial risks that have been accumulated over a
long period of time have begun to crop up now, it said, citing
increasing amounts of bad loans, the establishment of illegal
financial institutions, offering of illegal financial services,
excessive speculation in the stock market, and ineffective
financial supervision.
</P>
<P>
The financial risks have begun to appear now and drawn the
attention of the whole society because they have become more
apparent as China is shifting to a market economy, the article
said.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for China's mounting alertness against financial
risks is the recent financial crisis in Southeast Asia, according
to the article.
</P>
<P>
Under a planned economy that was pursued for decades,
state-owned enterprises relied too heavily on bank credits, which
eventually resulted in a large proportion of bad loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Calls for Measures to Prevent Financial Risks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Though there exist risks in the financial sector, China's
overall financial order is good and stable, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we should be confident in controlling and warding
off the risks," it said.
</P>
<P>
The confidence in resolving financial risks should be based,
first of all, on the sustained, rapid and sound growth of the
Chinese economy and on China's ever-increasing economic strength
and comprehensive national strength.
</P>
<P>
Since China carried out its market economic reforms in the late
1970s, its gross domestic product (GDP) has grown at an average
annual rate of 9.9 percent and the GDP has quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
"This is the strength with which we can prevent and ward off
financial risks," the article said.
</P>
<P>
The effective control over inflation is vital to the success of
China's efforts to prevent financial risks and maintain financial
stability, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Since the second half of 1993, China has brought inflation
under control, bringing the retail price index down to 6.1 percent in
1996 from 13.2 percent in 1993. This year the inflation rate has
dropped significantly.
</P>
<P>
In the years to come, China will continue to follow a moderately
tight monetary and fiscal policy to control inflation.
</P>
<P>
China's good balance of international payments is another
factor favorable to the prevention of financial risks, the article
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 China reported a current-account surplus of 7.24
billion US dollars, with trade surplus standing at 19.5 billion US
dollars. Its surplus under the capital account was 39.97 billion
US dollars last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Calls for Measures to Prevent Financial Risks (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves had reached 135 billion US
dollars by the end of November. At the same time both the amount
and structure of China's foreign investment and foreign debts are
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has utilized 320 billion US dollars in foreign
funds, including more than 200 billion US dollars in direct foreign
investment. Long-term debts account for more than 80
percent of China's foreign debts of 118 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"All this has provided a powerful support for a stable exchange
rate of the Chinese yuan and increased China's ability to resist
international speculation and counter the effects of international
financial turmoils," the article said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that in recent years China has formulated a series
of rules and regulations designed to standardize the financial
order, while the People's Bank of China, the central bank, has
accumulated a great deal of successful experiences in financial
supervision and preventing and warding off financial risks.
</P>
<P>
To prevent and minimize financial risks, financial institutions
should tighten self-control and the central bank should tighten
supervision over the country's financial sector, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China should quicken its pace to restructure its
economy and increase the public's awareness of financial
risks, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
