<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mysterious Disease Breaks Out in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious disease has
reportedly broken out in Somalia's southern region of Lower
Shabelle, taking the toll of scores of people in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Somali Red Crescent Society (SRCS) said the
disease is seen this week in Torotorow village, 115 km south of
the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The SRCS officials said the symptoms of the disease are high
fever, liver and stomach ache accompanied by blood spitting.
Victims of the disease die within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, 42 people have died of the disease
since the SRCS team visited Torotorow last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"When we reached the village on December 18, the community
elders told us that 330 people have died of the mysterious
disease," said one of the local SRCS workers. However, he said,
"The number seems to be a little bit exaggerated."
</P>
<P>
A health investigating team from the SRCS, the International
Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) and the World Health Organization
have left Mogadishu this morning for Torotorow village. The team
is expected to take stool and blood samples from the victims for
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
The SRCS officials couldn't confirm whether this disease
resembles or is identical to the enigmatic sickness that recently
broke out in northern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"We can't declare anything before laboratory tests prove us
anything," said the officials.
</P>
<P>
This fresh alarm of the mysterious disease coincides with a
deadly cholera situation in the capital and its surrounding areas
since heavy rains laid pools of water in the unhygienic city.
</P>
<P>
Local doctors announced this morning a serious shortage of the
sodium infusions for rehydrating the cholera victims in the
capital. At present, a bag of 0.5 liter of the sodium infusion
now costs nearly 14 U.S. Dollars in Mogadishu, which is 30 times
more expensive than its original price.
</P>
<P>
Dr Abdurahman Ali Awale (Dr Habeb) of Benadir Medical Center
in Mogadishu said nine children died of cholera Wednesday in his
clinic in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Dr Habeb announced that the cholera situation is now out of
hand when there's no single international aid agency dealing with
the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know what to do, people are just dying before us and
we can't do anything about it," he said, adding "Each child is
discharging two liters of his body liquid each time of vomiting
and loosing bowel."
</P>
<P>
The main SOS hospital in Mogadishu has stopped receiving
cholera patients unless it's very critical. SOS also stopped
giving out sodium infusions earlier offered to the patients for
rehydration.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the suspension is said to be related to an
incapability of the hospital to deal with the innumerable number
of cholera cases arriving at the hospital. All hospital wards and
outside gardens are now filled with patients.
</P>
<P>
A group of Somali doctors Wednesday voluntarily opened a
quarantine center in the former Maternity Hospital of Benadir
where more than 20 people had been registered since this morning.
Doctors said the only thing they have is to give out the Oral
Rehydration Solution.
</P>
<P>
Two international aid agencies, MSF-Spain and Action Contra la
Faim (French) are expected to return to the capital tomorrow to
open the first cholera quarantine center in the former Forlanini
Hospital of North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Rough statistics from the mother and child heath care posts in
Mogadishu indicate that since November 17, more than 254 people
have so far died of cholera in Mogadishu and its surrounding
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
