<HEADLINE> China's GDP Estimated to Increase By 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to have a
nine percent increase in Gross Domestic Product (GDP) this year,
a senior Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a national TV and telephone conference on commodity
circulation today, Chen Bangzhu, minister of the Internal Trade,
said that the country's total retail sales are estimated to go up
11 percent while the rise of retail prices will be under two
percent.
</P>
<P>
Marked progress has been made in chain-store business, the
minister noted, adding that at present, China has over 1,000
chain-store companies with 15,000 sales outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Business lines of these chain stores have been expanded from
consumer goods to machinery products and farm machines, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
In large and medium-sized cities, chain store sales have
accounted for more than five percent of the retail sales.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, among 151 large shopping centers and malls
surveyed, 45,7 percent reported a slumping business in the first
ten months, compared with the same period of last year, according
to an investigation conducted by the Commercial Information Center
under the ministry.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, initial headway has been made in the agent
system as is illustrated by this year's sales of steel products
and automobiles which have climbed 4.1 percent and 15.6 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the number of pilot steel makers which have
introduced the agent system have increased to 371.
</P>
<P>
Li Lanqing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee
and vice-premier of the State Council, made a written speech at
the conference, hoping that there would be new measures and
breakthroughs in the commodity circulation system next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
