<HEADLINE> Zambian Former President Detained by Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 25 (xinhua) -- Kenneth Kaunda, Zambia's
former president and leader of the country's biggest opposition
party -- the United National Independence Party (UNIP), was
detained by police in Lusaka early this morning.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by P.S. Chitambala, deputy Secretary for
Publicity and Information of UNIP, during an interview with
Xinhua at the Freedom House, the party's headquarters in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Chitambala, also a member of the UNIP central committee, said
Kaunda was arrested at his residence of Kalundu House in the Roma
district at about 6:00 hours local time this morning and put into
Kamwala Remand prison in Lusaka serving a detention order for
28 days.
</P>
<P>
The detention was made four days after Kaunda returned home
from a world tour following an abortive military coup in Zambia
on October 28 to overthrow the government. And in another
development, the police also arrested Kaunda's head of physical
security Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda is alleged to have been involved in the coup and his
arrest is believed to come sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
Chitambala claimed that soon after the detention, he tried to
enter the prison to find out what has happened to the "old man",
but was stopped by the police.
</P>
<P>
He accused President Frederick Chiluba of ill-treating Kaunda,
father of the nation who led Zambia to independence from the
British colonial rule in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the detention of Kaunda will
jeopardize the proposed inter-party talks between leaders of the
ruling Movement for Muti-Party Democracy (MMD) and the country's
about 30 opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory talks were held early this month to pave the way
for further official talks among presidents of all the political
parties scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party talks are designed to break the country's
political impasse over the constitutional provisions on the
election system since last year's general elections and to
promote national harmony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
