<HEADLINE> Forum Held on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned
enterprises, especially loss-making ones, can learn from the
experience of ten model enterprises to their own benefit, agreed
the attenders to a forum on reform of state-owned enterprises held
here today.
</P>
<P>
The forum was jointly organized by the Publicity Department of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the State
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials of departments of central authorities and
some enterprises, economists, and leading officials from major
media organizations based in the Chinese capital, attended the
forum.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the model enterprises' experience show that to
change from loss-making to profit-making, enterprises should
deepen the reform by resorting to the market, reorganizing the
work of their own personnel, readjusting organization and capital
structures, and enhancing management to bring out the potentials.
</P>
<P>
Low economic efficiency plaguing the state-owned sector has
become one of the biggest obstacles to China's further economic
development. To spread the experience of enterprises that have
successfully wriggled out of operational difficulties, the Chinese
media have widely carried reports on ten model enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The attenders believed that China will achieve its goal for the
reform and development of state-owned enterprises if the whole
Party and the whole nation seize the favorable chance rendered by
China's present economic and social development and fully and
correctly implement the gist of the 15th CPC National Conference
held three months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
