<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pledges Continued CITES Commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China has pledged to continue
fulfilling its commitment to the Convention on International Trade
in Endandered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) and make
greater efforts in wildlife protection and trade management.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made here today by Wang Zhibao, director of the
Chinese CITES Management Authority under the State Council, at a
national conference on wildlife export and import management.
</P>
<P>
China has been actively involved in CITES activities and has
taken various measures to protect its wildlife resource since it
became a CITES contracting party in 1981, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
To meet its commitment to CITES, China ceased exporting tusks
of Asian elephant and African elephant and ivories in 1986 and
1990. In 1993, it banned trading of rhinoceros horns and tiger
bones and stopped the production and sale of some traditional
Chinese medicines that used the horns and bones as ingredients.
</P>
<P>
It has concentrated on protecting its wildlife
resources. Wildlife traders must be licensed by the Chinese CITES
Authority, Wang said, adding that the country has prohibited using
wild rhesus monkey for experiments, vaccine production or for
export. Export of musks, snakes and snake products must get state
permission.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has limited the export of ready-made
traditional Chinese medicines that use wild plants and parts of
wild animals as ingredients, and the export of some wild animals
for meat and exhibition.
</P>
<P>
"China's effort to fulfill CITES commitment is also demonstrated
in its endeavors to save rare and endangered species," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 16 years, the country has established research
and breeding centers for such rare animals like wild horse, David's
deer, giant panda, Chinese alligator and Siberian Tiger. In
addition, it has set up a great many nature reserves for both
endangered animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese CITES Management Authority has joined hands with
police and customs in cracking down on wildlife smuggling and
illicit poaching and trading.
</P>
<P>
From 1995 to the first half of this year, forest police alone
crushed some 46,000 cases which involved about 430,000 wild
animals. More than 12,000 law violators were punished according to
law during the first six months of this year, Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
China boasts rich wildlife resources. It has over 4,800 kinds
of vertebra, or 10 percent of the world's total. With a pool of
30,000 kinds of higher plants on its vast territory, the country
ranks third in the world in this regard, after Brazil and
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
