<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Plans to Set Up More Soil Testing Labs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government has
planned to set up 17 more soil-testing laboratories at a cost of
800 million taka (about 17.78 million U.S. dollars), a press
report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The soil-testing labs, which are to be located in 17 districts'
headquarters, will help farmers of different localities test their
soil samples and apply required doses of organic and chemical
fertilizers in the fields.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are only five such labs in the country with
the central lab in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Planning Commission has already recommended
setting up of 10 soil-testing labs and asked the Soil Resources
Development Institute (SRDI) to prepare a revised project
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh has also set up two new research stations
-- watershed and soil conservation station, and soil and water
salinity management research center -- in two districts to check
soil erosion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
