<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Cancel Credit Quota System Starting Next Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China will abolish the credit
quota system starting next year, a significant move to the way
by which its central bank conducts financial macro control.
</P>
<P>
Beginning January 1, 1998, the credit quota ceiling system
governing the state-owned commercial banks will be phased out and
a new system of indirect control on the basis of
asset-to-liability management and risk management will be
implemented, the People's Bank of China (PBC), the central bank,
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The PBC next year will not issue mandatory loan plans to the
state-owned commercial banks and will instead issue "guiding"
plans on a yearly or quarterly basis, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The guiding plan, as a monitoring target for macro-economic
control by the central bank, will be used as a reference by the
state-owned commercial banks in compiling their respective funding
plans, it said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the state-owned commercial banks may decide for
their own the use of their funds in accordance with law and they
may extend loans in line with credit principles and relevant state
policies.
</P>
<P>
The banks may arrange their own loans for circulating
funds. Loans for investment in fixed assets promised before the
end of 1997 will continue to be honored, while new fixed-asset
loans will be decided and issued by respective banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
