<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 1.5 Tonnes of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian security forces seized
1.5 tonnes of morphine and opium extract from a truck loaded with
bricks in the central Isfahan province, Iran's official news
agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the provincial security forces Brigadier General
Mohammad Tayefi said six smugglers were arrested in the
operation. He did not give the date for the drug seizure.
</P>
<P>
Tayefi said that his forces seized 6.5 tonnes of various types
of narcotics during the first three quarters of the current
Iranian year (started March 21) and smashed 11 drug bands.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking poses a serious problem for the Iranian
government. Iran is one of the major transit routes for smugglers
to ship narcotics produced in the "Golden Crescent" in the border
areas of Iran, Pakistan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian anti-drug official earlier announced that the
country captured an average of 160 tonnes of various drugs
annually since it passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989 slapping
capital punishment on drug smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
