<HEADLINE> Hunan Adopts New Technique to Boost Rice Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Central-south China's Hunan
Province has increased by more than 1.5 billion kilograms of rice
in the past seven years by adopting rice seedling dry-nursing
technique.
</P>
<P>
The technique, introduced from Japan, has been popularized in
northeast and north China regions since the early 1980s, and
agricultural experts noted that the technique can raise
per-hectare rice output by about 600 kg.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Hunan Province, one of China's major agricultural
provinces, began to popularize the technique. The technique has
been applied to 1.2 million hectares in 1997 as against 47
hectares in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the Hunan Provincial Agricultural
Bureau, the province has spread the technique in 2.67 million
hectares over the past seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
