<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Zimbabwe Steps up Land Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhu Shixiang)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
released a list of 1,480 commercial farms for compulsory
acquisition and decided to redistribute these farms to landless
families in its efforts to accelerate the land resettlement
program.
</P>
<P>
At least 62,000 families have been resettled since
independence in 1980 but another 100,000 are still waiting for
the land which the government has been promising for the past 17
years.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1997 should be the final year for acquiring land.
The government has decided to compulsorily acquire over 1,500
farms or five million hectares of land to resettle about 100,000
landless families in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has vowed to fairly distribute the
land to the landless Zimbabweans who did not have enough land to
fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that only about 4,000 white farmers in the
country owned three-quarters of the best land at the expense of
the majority of Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe noted that the land apportionment
exercise is not meant to drive the white farmers out, but to
create an atmosphere which is conducive to the majority and the
white farmers still have a farm to live.
</P>
<P>
The list comprises farms belonging to individuals both white
and black, private companies and some government parastatals,
covering 45 of the total 54 districts. But most of the land will
come from white farmers.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said that the farmers will not be compensated for the
land but for the improvements they have made on the farms,
because ''land is the people's sovereign asset.''
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's land resettlement program hit a snag in 1989 when
Britain, which solely funded the program since 1980, withdrew its
assistance describing the initial program as a " failure".
</P>
<P>
However, the government went ahead and passed the Land
Acquisition Act of 1992, under which the state can compulsorily
acquire land, a step which has been slashed by western donors.
</P>
<P>
Since then negotiations between Zimbabwe and Britain to resume
the British funding for the resettlement program have not made
much progress as Zimbabwe refuses to meet the given conditions
including the willing-seller and willing-buyer scheme in
exercising the land resettlement program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
