<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Zimbabwe Steps up Land Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhu Shixiang)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Upon learning the list, the
landless Zimbabweans hailed the government's decision on the
resettlement program, saying their long-waited dream will become
true.
</P>
<P>
Over 5,000 delegates attending the annual national party
congress of the ruling ZANU (PF) this month unanimously adopted a
resolution supporting the program, saying it's a significant
decision for the country's economic development and poverty
eradication.
</P>
<P>
"Without such resettlement, it is unlikely that it can achieve
either long-term economic growth that will be satisfactory for
the majority of Zimbabweans, or long-term political stability,"
the daily The Herald said in a comment.
</P>
<P>
But the British press labelled the Zimbabwe government's
efforts to resolve the land imbalance as a "land grabbing
exercise".
</P>
<P>
"So, we are grabbing the land, but who started grabbing land
from the other? " asked Mugabe. "If you grab my property and I
follow you up and demand my property back, could that be termed
`grabbing'? "
</P>
<P>
At home, Zimbabwe's Commercial Farmers Union criticised the
designated farms, saying that most of the commercial farms listed
by the government for acquisition are not in the categories of
farms that were previously said to be acquired.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Farmers Union predicted that if the land
acquisition program is implemented, production value from
large-scale farming would drop from one billion U.S. dollars to
630 million dollars annually, with value of exports dropping 470
million U.S. Dollars from 700 million U.S.Dollars. The number of
workers on commercial farms would drop from 327,000 to 180,000.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Farmers Union has called on the government to
review the thorny issue of land designation, and consider
suspension of acquisition of about 240 of black-owned commercial
farms which appeared on the list.
</P>
<P>
Opposition National Democratic Union said it will take the
government to court over the designation of commercial farms
whose owners have only one farm.
</P>
<P>
"If the government continues to grab these farms, then we
shall have no alternative but to take the whole matter to court
so that justice must be seen to be done. Our lawyers were already
preparing heads of arguments."
</P>
<P>
But Land and Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai has declared
that the government would not compromise on the land acquisition
program.
</P>
<P>
"By July or August next year, we will have finished the legal
processes and after August we will start the allocation," the
minister promised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
