<HEADLINE> Nigerian Ministers Barred from Leaving Abuja </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's newly sworn in
cabinet members have been warned not to leave the capital Abuja
without proper clearance of the Head of State General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are also barred from employing personal
assistants, according to a circular dated December 22 which was
signed by Alhaji Gidado Idris, secretary to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The circular was issued one day after the uncovered coup plot
which involved the country's number two person, Chief of General
Staff Lieutenant-General Oladipo Diya, as well as 10 other
military officers and one civilian.
</P>
<P>
"I am directed to inform you that no minister should absent
himself from Abuja without first seeking and obtaining the
permission of the head of state, commander-in-chief," the circular
said.
</P>
<P>
No reason for the directive has been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
According to the circular, the head of state has stopped, with
immediate effect, the appointment and designation of special or
personal assistants to ministers and other government
functionaries.
</P>
<P>
"All such staff, wherever they are, must be relieved of their
appointments," it said, adding "ministers must learn to use the
services of the permanent secretaries and other government staff
who are already there to assist them."
</P>
<P>
To enforce the directive, Idris told the accountant-general
and auditor-general to stop paying the special assistants from
government funds.
</P>
<P>
The circular was addressed to the principal secretary of the
head of state, the inspector-general of police, ministers, heads
of permanent departments, permanent secretaries and
directors-general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
