<HEADLINE> 812 Raids on Israeli Forces in S. Lebanon in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese resistance forces
have launched some 812 attacks against Israeli forces and their
ally - the South Lebanese Army (SLA), this year, Lebanese
newspaper the Beirut Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an annual report of the United Nations
Interim Forces in south Lebanon (UNIFIL) on military activities in
south Lebanon as saying that some 765 attacks were carried out by
the Iranian-backed Hezbollah since the beginning of this year to
December 23.
</P>
<P>
The Amal Movement led by Lebanon's House Speaker Nabih Berri
was responsible for 44 attacks, the Syrian National Social Party
for two, and the Palestinian Islamic Jihad for one, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 39 Israeli and 22 SLA soldiers were
killed, and 95 Israeli and 70 SLA soldiers wounded this year in
fighting with Lebanese resistance guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the Islamic resistance suffered 66 deaths
and 27 injuries. The Lebanese Army had six fatalities and 10
casualties in skirmishes with Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Israeli attacks on residential areas killed 48 Lebanese
civilians and injured 130 others in 1997, the report added.
</P>
<P>
In an analysis of its own losses this year, UNIFIL said that
the crash of a helicopter near Tyre, the country's southern port
city near the Israeli occupied zone, in August of this year,
claimed four Italian and one Irish soldiers. Six Irish soldiers
were also killed by a roadside mine in south Lebanon last June.
</P>
<P>
The 5,400-strong UNIFIL was established in south Lebanon in
March 1978 after Israel's invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But it could not prevent the nearly everyday conflict between
Israeli troops and Lebanese resistance groups fighting to oust an
estimated 2,000 Israeli occupation troops.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers and the 2,500-strong SLA are jointly
patrolling the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone carved by
Israel in 1985 to protect its northern towns from cross-border
guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
