<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coal Industry Becomes Profitable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China's key coal mines have
succeeded in turning loss into profit in general this year,
expecting to produce 200 million yuan in profits.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Senhao, minister of coal industry, the
country's key coal mines have reversed in general the money-losing
situation which troubled the coal industry for 13 consecutive
years since 1984.
</P>
<P>
To date, some 70 percent of the country's 93 key coal mines
have become profitable, a sharp contrast to merely 9.7 percent in
1992.
</P>
<P>
The minister expects the country's coal mines to produce 1.33
billion tons of coal and export 31 million tons of coal this year.
</P>
<P>
More noteworthy, China's coal mines have become more intensive
in the economic growth mode, with their staff cut by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997, some 870,000 workers and staff in the key
coal mines have been laid off or transferred to other jobs.
</P>
<P>
And the diversified economic operation has contributed a lot to
the sound development of coal mines this year, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the country's coal-related diversified
economic enterprises have grown to 17,000, employing over 1.8
million personnel in total.
</P>
<P>
The minister expect these diversified economic enterprises to
produce output value and economic returns totalling 44.5 billion
yuan, or 57 percent of the total output value produced by all the
coal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0065 </DOCNO>
