<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law-makers Examine Draft of Price Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Participants to the ongoing
29th session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, China's top legislature, agree that the
revised draft of Price Law is roughly ripe to be passed at the
current session.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that the draft of Price Law is submitted
to NPC Standing Committee session for examination. The law is
aimed at regulating pricing and improve China's socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Law-makers Lai Jinlie and Sun Tingfang shared the view that
such a law is badly needed in China to regulate pricing and
stabilizing the market.
</P>
<P>
There are some gap between domestic and international prices,
and domestic prices should go in line with international prices
when necessary, so as to protect the initiative of both producers
and marketing people and prevent the loss of funds, they said.
</P>
<P>
Law-makers Wang Bingqian and Xia Jiajun said that the law
should enhance supervision over the pricing in service trades.
</P>
<P>
The prices of some free-trading commodities should not go
beyond control, and tips in some service trades should be given in
accordance with certain standards, law-maker Ye Zhengda said.
</P>
<P>
Law-maker Qin Zhongda noted that the law should add detailed
regulations on seeking staggering profits, dumping and monoply.
</P>
<P>
Another law-maker Dong Fureng suggested that the law have
articles restraining the abuse of power by government
functionaries at the time of conducting price inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Rulers in Nigeria Briefed About Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's influential
traditional rulers said Wednesday that they believed there was a
coup attempt in the country after they were shown video clippings
and audio recordings of preliminary investigations into it.
</P>
<P>
The documentary evidence was shown to a group of traditional
rulers across the country during a four-hour meeting with Head of
State General Sani Abacha at the presidential villa on Wednesday
in Abuja, the capital.
</P>
<P>
The clip seemed to have taken effect as the Ewi of Ado-Ekiti,
Oba Rufus Adejugbe Adeyemo condemned the coup attempt on behalf
of the royal fathers at the end of the meeting last night.
</P>
<P>
"From what we have heard from audio recordings and video
images of the preliminary investigations, we wish to condemn the
dastardly acts conceived and attempted by the plotters already
arrested," he said, quoted by local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Describing what would have been the result of the coup plot as
"the calamity that would have befallen the nation", he said:
"Nigeria would continue to survive and has indeed survived this
one, once again".
</P>
<P>
After reading a prepared text, the royal father did not
entertain reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the electronic images and recordings were
also played to members of the Provisional Ruling Council, the
country's highest policy making body, at Tuesday night's
emergency meeting which lasted till the early hours of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Chief David Attah, Chief Press Secretary to the
head of state, the briefing session with traditional rulers and
leaders of thought was one in the series of consultations by the
federal government to establish credibility for the alleged coup
plot.
</P>
<P>
Such consultations with representatives of the media are
expected to take place soon.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the National Council of State made up
of chief executives of the 36 states across the country began a
meeting in Abuja last night.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction to claims that the coup attempt was a frame
up, Attah said it was very disturbing that people had jumped to
conclusions even when such conclusions were at variance with
evidence "which some people were already privy to".
</P>
<P>
In his goodwill message to Nigerians on the Christmas eve,
Abacha called on the people to show brotherly love, humility,
tolerance, selflessness and dedication to their duty.
</P>
<P>
He also promised the people that the new year will witness
momentous events in the socio-economic and political spheres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
