<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time, the trade unions joined the groups of
unemployed workers in launching a spectacular action on Christmas
Eve Wednesday by seizing the National Agency of Employment ANPE in
Paris, which followed several similar actions across France. The
anti-unemployment groups call for the payment of a premium for the
end of the year to the unemployed workers through a social fund
frozen by the government.
</P>
<P>
-- The Mexican authorities were blamed for the massacre of 46
Tzotzile Indians, including 21 women and 15 children in a small
school and a poor church on a hill in Atenal in the remote region
of Chiapas on Tuesday. Paramilitary men associated with the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party attacked the Indians with
automatic weapons and axes when they were praying for peace on the
eve of Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The death of two youths who were killed by police last week
in the suburbs of Lyon and Fontainbleau has put into question the
government policy on development of city suburbs, where the
trilogy of youths, violence and suburbs are always linked
together. Jean-Pierre Sueur, former state secretary in charge of
local communities, said that he suggested to the government the
reduction of the number of new economic development zones in city
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
-- The international financial community made another effort on
Wednesday to save South Korea from collapse by providing another
package of eight billion U.S. dollars contributed by the Group of
Seven (G-7) industrialized nations and six other nations. 
</P>
