<HEADLINE> Winners of China Science Awards Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China announced here today the
1997 winners of state-level science awards which includes science
and technology advancement, natural science and technological
invention.
</P>
<P>
Hui Yongzheng, Vice Minister of the State Science and
Technology Commission (SSTC), said more than 3,700 scientists,
including several from Hong Kong, won awards for 626 scientific
and technological research programs.
</P>
<P>
He said 475 projects won state science and technology
advancement awards this year, which includes the design and
building of the 300,000-kilowatt Qinshan Nuclear Power Station.
</P>
<P>
The development of a kind of high-yield cotton seed won top
prize in the technological invention award. Another 99 projects
also won technological invention awards.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said the symplectic algorithms for
Hamiltonian systems -- an abstruse mathematical research program,
made by Feng Kong, a late academician of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, and his colleagues -- won this year's top prize of the
natural science award.
</P>
<P>
He explained that it is the second time since 1990 that Chinese
scientists won the top prize in the annual state natural science
award.
</P>
<P>
Hui said that, among the 51 natural science awards projects,
four were completed by Hong Kong scientists.
</P>
<P>
Henry N.C. Wong, professor in the Chemical Department of the
the Chinese University of Hong Kong, won a second prize in the
natural science category for his 17-year research program.
</P>
<P>
The official also announced the two winners of the
international science and technology cooperation award. They are
Arthur S. M. Lin, a Singapore eye expert, and Jean Pierre Lebrun,
a Frenchman and senior staff member of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The awards ceremony is scheduled for Friday afternoon in the
Great Hall of the People.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
