<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Willing to Improve Ties With Iran: Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said that he has longed for turning over a new leaf in relations
with Tehran, local newspaper Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the London-based Lebanese weekly
al-Hawadeth Wednesday, Mubarak said he has wanted to improve ties
with Iran since he assumed office 16 years ago,
</P>
<P>
The two countries severed diplomatic ties in 1979 after the
Islamic revolution topple shah's regime in Tehran and Egypt signed
peace with Israel in the U.S.-brokered Camp David peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
The victorious clergymen in Iran have been adamant in opposing
any peace efforts with Israel, which they denounce as "the Zionist
usurper" and refuse to give official recognition.
</P>
<P>
"So far some people are still reluctant to understand what Camp
David is," Mubarak said. "It was a mere general framework of
principles with two papers, the first on the Egyptian issue, and
the second on the Palestinian issue," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Had the Palestinians accepted to start negotiations on the Camp
David principles, the situation in the region would have been
completely different, Mubarak added.
</P>
<P>
The Camp David framework, he explained, imposed an Israeli
troop withdrawal to certain points outside the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. "The Israelis accepted this item. Today there is a great
argument on the redeployment of the Israeli troops on 8-10
percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Egypt have been improving. Mubarak
said that he sent his Foreign Minister Amr Moussa to Tehran
earlier this month to attend the eighth Islamic summit, "is a
clear signal."
</P>
<P>
Tehran had expected Mubarak's presence at the gathering of
world Islamic leaders and hoped it would lead to a breakthrough in
bilateral relations, now at the level of interest sections.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the Tehran Islamic summit is "successful to
a great extent" and hoped "all the resolutions the summit issued
be implemented."
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi had said Iran is working
towards restoring full diplomatic relations with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Iran and Egypt are getting closer to each other
and ... we found Egypt to be much closer to Iran," he said, when
speaking to reporters late Tuesday at the Athens airport winding
up his visit to Greece.
</P>
<P>
When asked if there was any timetable set for restoring
relations, he said "we are trying to take steps in that direction
and I am very hopeful that we can arrive at some conclusion in the
near future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
