<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Diamond Exports to SE Asia Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel's diamond exports to
Southeast Asia fell by 30-40 percent this year, which caused a
loss of more than 600 million U.S. dollars in revenues, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post quoted Israel's industry sources as saying
that the tumbling currencies, higher interest rates and slower
economic growth in Southeast Asia led to the decline of Israel's
diamond exports to the region.
</P>
<P>
The sources also predicted the situation will worsen next year
with higher losses due to diamond exports falling further.
</P>
<P>
Tzafrir Anbar, the diamond controller in the Ministry of
Industry and Trade, stressed that "we don't predict that the
situation will improve in the near term or next year."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the decrease in sales to Southeast Asia have had a
negative impact on the cash flow of the whole Israeli diamond
industry because the Asian customers usually pay in cash.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the cash flows (to Israel) have slowed makes the
banks nervous, which in turn hurts the whole industry," said an
Israeli trader.
</P>
<P>
Israel's exports volume of polished diamonds in 1996 stood at
5.3 billion dollars, accounting for about 25 percent of the total
exports volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
