<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets Auto Manufacturing Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Volkswagen
Corp., a Sino-German joint venture, produces one Santana car every
2.5 minutes this year, setting a record in China's auto
manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
The venture produced 211,700 cars in the first 11 months of
this year, up 15.4 percent on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Since the corporation was founded in 1985 it has turned out
900,000 Santana cars. In 1996, it became the largest industrial
firm in Shanghai in terms of sales volumes, by surpassing the
Baoshan Iron and Steel Complex.
</P>
<P>
The city has so far invested 700 million U.S. dollars in the
establishment of the Shanghai-General Motors Corp. Ltd., a
Sino-U.S. joint venture.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the annual production capacity of Shanghai should hit
400,000 cars. On average, a car will roll off the production line
every 1.5 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
