<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Public Hospitals Launch General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel's public hospitals
today began an open-ended strike to protest against planned
changes in the National Health Insurance law, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of doctors, nurses and administrative workers of the
hospitals left their jobs this morning, and only emergency
services and vital neonatal, dialysis and obstetrics departments
are still functioning normally.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in an attempt to prevent the Knesset (parliament)
from approving the changes in the law, directors of all the
country's public hospitals and senior health system administrators
will demonstrate today outside the Knesset building.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes, as part of the Treasury-sponsored
arrangements bill for the state budget of 1998, would allow each
health fund to set its own basket of services, allow insurers to
charge extra for a wide variety of services and eliminate
long-term geriatric nursing care from health fund responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Peterburg, director-general of the country's public
hospitals, said Wednesday that the changes will bring about the
establishment of two separate health systems - one for the
well-off and another for lower income groups.
</P>
<P>
He noted that under the new law the average family will have to
pay over 1,000 shekels (about 280 dollars) extra annually for
visits to doctors, hospital emergency rooms, outpatient clinics
and other services.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Health Ministry Director-General Gabi Barabash also
expressed hope that the Knesset members will vote against the
proposals in the plenary session scheduled at the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
He noted that transferring responsibility for preventive
health services to the health funds would be disastrous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
