<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Cooperation With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran has denied Israeli press
reports about its cooperation with Israel and involvement in
terrorist acts, calling them ploys of the "Zionist regime."
</P>
<P>
Tehran Radio said today Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mahmoud Mohammadi Wednesday night refuted the reports on
Iranian-Israeli cooperation and Iran's sponsoring of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said such moves were designed by the "negative propaganda of
Israeli Zionist circles" and their anxieties over the success of
Tehran summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
on December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
The successful holding of the OIC summit and its highly
positive effects on the Islamic world prompted the Zionist
propaganda apparatus (press) to embark on negative propaganda to
overshadow the fruitful outcome of the summit, Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
"The unity and concurrence among Islamic countries and the
presence of high-ranking Islamic leaders in Tehran have made the
Zionist regime to resort to these futile efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that "the Islamic Republic of Iran does not
officially recognize Israel." The late shah of Iran had been on
good terms with Israel but Tehran broke off all ties with what it
called "Zionist usurper" after the victory of Islamic Revolution
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also dismissed reported statements by U.S.
ambassador to Israel about Iran's involvement in the massacre of
tourists in Luxor, Egypt, saying the remarks were in line with
Israel's concern over Tehran-Cairo rapprochement during the OIC
summit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador, however, said he would neither confirm the
report, nor deny it.
</P>
<P>
In last month's Luxor terrorist attack, 58 foreign tourists and
four Egyptians were killed, dealing a severe blow to Egypt's
lucrative tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Such familiar ploys can not halt the growing trend of
anti-Zionist sentiments in the Islamic world, the spokesman
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
