<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah's Agent Faces Trial in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A German citizen sent by
Hezbollah to launch a suicide attack in Israel was put on trial
today in the Tel Aviv Magistrates Court.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security officials revealed that Stefan Josef Smirak, a
convert to Islam, was arrested on November 28 upon his arrival at
the Ben-Gurion Airport.
</P>
<P>
Smirak, 26, was allegedly recruited by Hezbollah, which has
been waging a guerrilla war against Israeli occupation of south
Lebanon, in a visit to Lebanon between August and November this
year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, Smirak was sent to a training camp in the
Bekka Valley in Lebanon, where he was taught to use light weapons
and operate explosive devices, the Israeli police said.
</P>
<P>
It said Smirak was provided with video cameras and electronic
communication devices and sent to Israel to collect information
and to film densely populated areas in Tel Aviv and Haifa in order
to target a site for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah handlers in Lebanon also demanded Smirak change his
passport in order to erase any traces of his Lebanese visit
before travelling to Israel. Once he finished the fact-finding
mission, he planned to fly to Turkey and contact his handlers to
finalize the plan for carrying out the suicide attack, police
added.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time that Hezbollah has attempted to send
agents into Israel to launch attacks. In May 1996, Israeli
security forces arrested a Lebanese citizen carrying a forged
British passport in a Jerusalem hotel, where he seriously injured
himself when the bomb he was preparing exploded in his room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
