<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half of China's Provincial Boundaries Demarcated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Almost half of the provincial
boundaries in China have been demarcated, according to a national
demarcation conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
China now has 31 provinces and autonomous regions (excluding
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and Taiwan Province).
Between them are 68 boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Sources attending the conference said 33 provincial boundaries
with a combined length of more than 20,000 kilometers, or 43.5
percent of the total, have been demarcated.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 136,000 kilometers of inter-county boundaries were
marked in the last two years. The length accounts for 34
percent of the entire inter-county boundaries.
</P>
<P>
For thousands of years in the Chinese history, the central
governments had not carried out such a national boundary
demarcation, resulting in a lot of boundary disputes, said
Jin Ergang, who works with a leading group on demarcation under
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
As population grows and demands for natural resources increase,
the boundary problems are becoming more obvious, he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Council decided in November of 1995 that land
boundaries between provinces and counties would be marked within
five years, beginning from 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The demarcation is aimed at settling the current boundary disputes
and preventing new ones, and providing legal evidence
for resolving future disputes," said Li Guixian, state councillor
and director of the leading demarcation group.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes smoothly, 70 percent of the boundaries
between provinces will have been marked by the end of 1998, said
Li Baoku, vice-minister of civil affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0099 </DOCNO>
