<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Treatment for Prostate Cancer Developed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 25 (Xinhua) -- An implant containing a
compound that suppresses the production of testosterone in men
has been developed by an Israeli-American team to treat
metastasizing prostate cancer, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The implant, which is inserted into the skin, was developed by
Professor Irving Spitz of Jerusalem's Shaare Zedek Hospital with
scientists from the Population Council in New York.
</P>
<P>
Implanting the 2.6-centimeter long capsule under the skin on
the inner part of the arm is a simple procedure.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the metastasizing prostate cancer has been treated
by castration or quarterly injections of testosterone suppressors,
which are painful and inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
Spitz, who heads the hospital's hormone research institute,
said this type of prostate cancer is the first type of tumor
proven to be connected with hormone production.
</P>
<P>
Such new treatment has been used in clinical studies on 34
patients, and it is also being tested at the Cornell University
and the University of Salzburg in the U.S.. But it could take two
years for it to gain approval from the United States Food and Drug
Administration, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
