<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Warns Tanzania on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The International
Monetary Fund (IMF) has urged the Tanzanian government to reduce
inflation and speed up the pace of privatization, and warned that
the economy is vulnerable to external shocks.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the country's economy, the IMF said it expected
economic growth in Tanzania to rise to 4.7 percent in 1997/98
from 3.9 percent in 1996/97, and inflation to decline to 13
percent from 17.1 percent, Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the Tanzanian authorities should aim for "further
strong declines" in inflation in the coming year, and should
accelerate the government's privatization program. It regretted
that the privatization program has not moved as fast as
planned over the last year.
</P>
<P>
The government should also eliminate its arrears and carry out
proposed tax reforms, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming steps taken in the government's 1997/98
budget, the IMF said authorities must be "vigilant" and should
be prepared to take further action if needed to meet their fiscal
targets.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania's economy remains vulnerable to external shocks,"
such as a drop in demand for exports, a rise in the price of
imports, or a shift in investor sentiment, the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
