<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea will receive emergency loans from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the Group of Seven
industrialized nations to help it out of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Lim Chang-yuel, the South Korean minister of finance and
economy, said the two organizations have agreed to provide 10
billion U.S. dollars to South Korea, which is sorely in need of
foreign aid to bail out the world's 11th largest economy. The IMF
would provide two billion dollars and the rest of the money would
come from the Group of Seven, he added. (IMF-SKorea-G7)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The U.N. Sanctions Commission (UNSCOM) on Iraq
Wednesday issued a permission for a Russian aircraft to continue
its flight to Baghdad, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tupolev-204, with five tons of medicine and 23 Russian
parliament members and specialists on board, was stopped by the
Iranian authority from entering Iraq via Iranian airspace, for
lack of U.N. authorization. UNSCOM agreed to the plane's flight to
Baghdad after it obtained detailed information about the cargo
aboard from Russian government. (Iran-Russian Plane-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The fired postal worker who held seven people
hostage at a regional mail center in Denver surrendered on
Christmas Eve after a nine and a half hour standoff with police.
</P>
<P>
Davis Lee Jackson, 42, surrendered at about 5:00 p.m. local
time (19:00 EST). The hostages were released unharmed, reports
from Denver said. Jackson allegedly got into the building shortly
after 7:00 a.m. local time with a shotgun, possibly through
loading docks and held the hostages in a supervisor's office in
the mail sorting building, police said. (US-Hostage-Surrender)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- The Bulgarian Ministry of Education and Science
announced Wednesday that from next year on students will have more
options in learning foreign languages, Chinese included.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers, primary school students can
choose one from English, French, German, Italian, Spanish and
Russian as their first foreign language after entering school. In
the fifth year, the students will be asked to learn a second
foreign language, Chinese, Japanese and Portuguese are on the
optional list. Thus, they will have grasped the basic knowledge of
two foreign languages when graduating from middle schools.
(Bulgaria-Chinese Language) 
</P>
