<HEADLINE> Vietnam PM Urges Fight Against Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister
Nguyen Tan Dung says Vietnam has to fight against smuggling in
order to maintain its nine percent economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a conference on Tuesday in Ho Chi Minh
city to promote the campaign against smuggling by sea, air and at
border gates.
</P>
<P>
He said the anti-smuggling campaign should be carried out by
all authorities and sectors, starting from grassroots, and he
emphasised the importance of anti-smuggling propaganda in the mass
media.
</P>
<P>
Phan Van Dinh, the general director of Vietnam's General
Department of Customs and the chairman of Vietnam's Government
Committee On Fighting Smuggling, said Vietnam's 1,200 kilometers
south-west border with Cambodia had serious problems of
smuggling. Many people used bicycles, motor-bikes, trucks, cars
and boats to carry illegal goods into the country.
</P>
<P>
last year, Vietnam's anti-smuggling agency uncovered almost
5,000 cases of smuggling and 1,167 people were arrested,
representing an 11 percent increase over 1995. 
