<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Reduce Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 24 (Xinhua) --Ukraine will reduce its armed
forces by 12 percent by the end of 1998, a senior military officer
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It plans cut back its forces by 75,000 men next year, of which
37,000 will be officers, Major General Nikolai Matyukh, director
of the Bureau of Mobilization of the Armed Forces, told a news
briefing held here.
</P>
<P>
Under the order of President Leonid Kuchma, who also serves as
the commander-in-chief of the armed forces, the Defense Ministry
will take measures to whittle its forces to 400,000.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe the plan will cause some new problems for the
country such as the need for housing and pensions for the
demobilized soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate Ukraine needs to increase expenditure up to
700 million hryvna (about 370 million U.S. dollars) to solve these
problems. 
</P>
