<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salas Remains Till Next Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's River Plate
striker Marcelo Salas, rumored to be transferred to Europe in a
multi-million dollar deal, will remain with the team until after
the World Cup, his agent said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
His agent, Gustavo Mascardi told reporters that even if the
Chilean star was sold, it would be on condition that he plays for
River next season. The next Argentine tournament ends in July.
</P>
<P>
Mascardi denied reports that River had accepted a bid of more
than 30 million U.S. dollars from Italy's Lazio. But he said
representatives from both clubs had met to discuss the player's
future.
</P>
<P>
Salas, who turned 23 on Wednesday, has become South American
soccer's hottest property since moving to River Plate last year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, he scored two goals to lead River Plate to
win South American's Super Cup against Brazil's Sao Paulo with
2-1. Four days later, he scored the goal which clinched River's
third straight league title in a 1-1 draw with Argentinos Juniors.
</P>
<P>
England's Manchester United was one of the first clubs to
express an interest in Salas, and manager Alex Ferguson traveled
to Chile to watch him on international duty. The club has recently
said they will not pursue their interest.
</P>
<P>
Mascardi said Salas prefers a move to Italy. AC Milan and Parma
are believed to be among the top clubs vying for him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
