<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 06:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Plane Allowed to Fly to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Sanctions Commission
(UNSCOM) on Iraq Wednesday issued a permission for a Russian
aircraft to continue its flight to Baghdad, Iran's official news
agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Tupolev-204, with five tonnes of medicine and 23 Russian
parliament members (MPs) and specialists on board, was stopped by
the Iranian authority from entering Iraq via Iranian airspace, for
lack of U.N. authorization.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM agreed to the plane's flight to Baghdad after it
obtained detailed information about the cargo aboard from Russian
government.
</P>
<P>
However, IRNA did not mention if the Russian plane has left for
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Russian plane was reportedly scheduled to land in Iraq
Wednesday by attempting to sidestep UNSCOM. It had asked for
approval from Azerbaijan and Iran to pass through their airspace,
instead of requesting a U.N. permit.
</P>
<P>
The plane was held up by the Iranian authority citing it would
defy the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Tehran proposed to the U.N. that it deliver the Russian
shipments of medicine to Iraq through a land route.
</P>
<P>
"Sending the cargo through air would only be possible through
special U.N. authorization," Iran's Foreign Ministry said Tuesday,
and "it is natural that Iran continues to abide by U.N. sanctions
regulations on Iraq."
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. sanctions imposed on after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990, no plane can fly into Iraq except those of
U.N. carrying food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The flight of Russian plane was an initiative of Russia's
ultra-nationalist MP and head of the Liberal Democratic Party
Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
</P>
<P>
He has strongly criticized the crippling U.N. sanctions on
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
