<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Gets Emergency "Christmas" Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will receive
emergency loans from the International Monetary Fund and the Group
of Seven industrialized nations to help it out of the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Lim Chang-yuel, the South Korean minister of finance and
economy, said the two organizations have agreed to provide 10
billion U.S. dollars to South Korea, which is sorely in need of
foreign aid to bail out the world's 11th largest economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF would provide two billion dollars and the rest of the
money would come from the Group of Seven, he added.
</P>
<P>
"I may say these are the Christmas gifts to Korean people from
our allies," he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements with Seoul, the world financial institution
will provide 57 billion dollars in rescue loans to the country,
whose crisis has been caused by the failure of conglomerates, and
bad loans by financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
In return for the loans, the IMF demands that South Korea
completely open its domestic securities market, close down ailing
commercial banks and abolish all restrictions over foreigners'
investments in its bond markets.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the country's economy could grind to a halt
without these huge loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
