<HEADLINE> Solar Energy Brightens Village Life in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- No power stations. No
transmission cables. However, Monchunggong Village in Tibet is
ablaze with lights when night falls. The villagers say they have
sunlight at night.
</P>
<P>
Monchunggong is the first village to install solar energy since
the Tibet Autonomous Region launched its "sunlight program" in
1992. The village is located at the foot of Yungbulhakhang Palace,
the first palace ever in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Tibet invested 200,000 yuan and equipped 20 families
in the village with solar energy apparatus, which was provided by
the State Science and Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Nyima Cering family of eight now can make blankets at home
with the aid of electric lights. "It's fantastic," they said. "The
solar energy enables us to do farm work during the day and to make
rugs at night. We earn 20,000-30,000 yuan each year because of
that."
</P>
<P>
Nyoidrub, a 72-year-old family member, now can do her
needlework under the lights powered by solar energy. "I just
cannot believe it," she said. "It happened, and is really fresh to
me."
</P>
<P>
Nyoidrub is so proud of the solar energy that she even takes
visitors to the roof to view the apparatus. And she knows how it
works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Energy Brightens Village Life in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sixteen families in the village now are making carpets or
processing agricultural products at nights, according to Zhaxi,
head of the village.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi said that in the past many people had to chat or just
sleep at night. Now, many study instead. Villagers often gather to
watch videos on technical information to learn about science, to
farm with new technology and to trade with information.
</P>
<P>
Villagers also can watch movies such as "Tunnel Warfare." They
used to walk 10 miles to watch a film, but now see movies seven or
eight times each month. Our life is much richer, they say.
</P>
<P>
Village life is no longer dark. In the brightly lighted village
women are busy with needlework, kids concentrate on their homework
and families are hand-weaving rugs.
</P>
<P>
Two more villages will be involved in the program in the area
next year, according to an official of the science and technology
committee in the southern part of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Solar energy is expected to spread throughout the whole
southern area of 300,000 residents. The program's goal is to
install 70,000 solar-energy stoves to help solve fuel problems and
one million square meters of solar-energy greenhouses to grow
vegetables for one-fifth of the population in Tibet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
