<HEADLINE> Survey Suggests Rise in Profitability for India's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The performance of the
Indian corporate sector in the first half of 1997-98 (from April
to September) suggests diverse trends in profitability for
consumer-oriented items and the core sectors, according to a
survey available here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Investment Research and
Information Services LTD for the Associations Council of the
Confederation of Indian Industry (CII), has covered 465 companies
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The sectors like consumer durables, food and food processing,
paints, cigarettes, tea and coffee have recorded a significant
increase in their net profit figure in comparison with the first
half of 1996-97, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
However, the core sectors like petrochemicals, power, steel,
information technology (hardware) and telecom equipment have
witnessed an erosion in their profitability.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the survey has revealed that the corporate sector of
India had been in reasonably good health in the first half of
1997-98. The net profit figure of the 465 companies surveyed
increased by 15.7 percent during the period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
