<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees Minor Rise in Tourist Arrivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand recorded 5.27 million
tourist arrivals between January and September this year, up 0.95
percent compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand saw the minor growth in tourist arrivals during the
first nine months mainly due to several months of haze in
Southeast Asia and the regional economic turmoil, according to
recent reports from the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT).
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals from East Asia, one of the most significant
markets for Thailand, posted a 1.34 percent of increase and they
were mainly sources contributing to the tiny rise of tourist
arrivals in Thailand during the period.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from New Zealand and Australia also grew.
</P>
<P>
However, tourists from most other markets dropped.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from Europe, another major market for Thailand, saw a
0.07 percent decrease during the period, with less tourists from
seven of the 15 European Union members, including Germany, Italy,
and France.
</P>
<P>
The TAT said that the European market was affected mainly by
many months of news reports about the haze.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from South Asia dropped significantly by 15.2 percent
during the period and the TAT attributed this to the tight visa
conditions by Thailand as well as the economic and political
problems in the countries.
</P>
<P>
The TAT predicted that the tourist arrivals for the whole year
of 1997 would reach 7.26 million, up around one percent compared
with last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
