<HEADLINE> Moody's Move Adds to Thailand's Woes: Ex-minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Moody's downgrading of
Thailand's foreign currency credit has added to the growing
skepticism of many countries about Thailand's creditworthiness,
former Thai finance minister Thanong Bidaya said.
</P>
<P>
Moody's announcement early this week that Thailand's foreign
currency credit for bonds and notes was reduced to junk status has
made many countries hesitant about providing further assistance to
Thailand, the Bangkok Post Thursday quotes Thanong as saying.
</P>
<P>
The downgrading will frighten away potential foreign capital
inflows, resulting in lack of foreign cash to shore up liquidity
and dampening the country's economic rescue efforts, Thanong said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to prepare cushions for more severe
economic shock waves next year when many more businesses are
expected to close down.
</P>
<P>
He said the government must think of ways of sustaining the
ailing industrial and financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the government to weigh the pros and cons of
making important economic decisions, as it might have to go
against public sentiment in order to protect the national
interests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy prime minister and commerce minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said on Wednesday that the country's highest economic
growth rate for 1998 would be zero.  
</P>
</TEXT>
