<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland's Agricultural Output Increases Amid Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Poland's agriculture maintained
a good yield despite three years of disaster, such as floods and a
cold climate in spring.
</P>
<P>
According to the Polish Central Statistics Bureau, Poland's
grain output reached 24.9 million tons, or 1.5 million tons more
than the average output in the 1991-1995 period and a 0.1 percent
increase over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rapeseed yields registered an increase of 100,000 tons over
that of 1996 to 600,000 tons, but still 34.7 percent less than the
average output in the 1991-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
The beet output reached 15.7 million tons, a 24.3 percent
increase over the 1991-1995 average, but 12.1 percent lower than
that of 1996, mainly due to the reduced sowing acreage caused by
less orders from sugar refineries.
</P>
<P>
But the potato output suffered a loss of 6.4 million tons to
20.8 million tons, a decrease of 23.7 percent compared with the
previous year as a result of the hot and humid climate in summer
and the rampant insects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
