<HEADLINE> Banks to Launch SPV for Revival of Sick Indian Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 25 (Xinhua)-- Some leading Indian banks and
top European banks have come together to launch a special purpose
vehicle (SPV) aimed at buying sick Indian firms, turning them
around and selling them within three to five years, the Business
standard said today.
</P>
<P>
A Mumbai (Bombay)-based firm of chartered accountants will
advise the SPV on the tax implications of the cross-border
transactions and help identify target loss-making companies with
turnaround potential.
</P>
<P>
The firm will also act as a kind of owner-consultant to sick
companies after their management is taken over by the SPV, the
local economic newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Banks would be interested in investing in the SPV as many of
the loans advanced by them to sick companies, which have been
classified as non-performing assets, can be salvaged if the SPV
takes over the companies and turns them around, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that discussions with leading banks and
institutions are at an advanced stage. These banks and
institutions are expected to contribute strongly to the investor
consortium of funds under the SPV.  
</P>
</TEXT>
