<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Arrests Nine Massacre Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Mexico police have
arrested nine suspects in connection with the Monday massacre of
45 indigenous people in the southern state of Chiapas, a top
justice official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Madrazo pledged the crimes would not go unpunished after
dispatching a team of eight investigators, seven ballistics
experts and 40 federal policemen to the state.
</P>
<P>
The government believed the assailants were from neighboring
communities of the poverty-stricken state that also houses the
country's best-known anti-government guerrilla group, the
Zapatista rebels, the general prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels there, however, blamed the massacre on the
government.
</P>
<P>
A gang of masked gunmen, wielding assault rifles, on Monday
killed 21 women, nine men, 14 children and one infant who were
fleeing violence from other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he was much
shocked by the mass murder, his spokesman Fred Echhard said in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Mexico has six million full-blooded indigenous people in its
population of 90 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
