<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Blame Government for Chiapas Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Zapatista rebels
Wednesday blamed President Ernesto Zedillo and his government for
the massacre of 45 people in the southern state of Chiapas two
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
In a four-page communique, the Zapatista leader, Subcommandante
Marcos, said the direct responsibility for this bloody event rests
on the president and the Interior Ministry who "two years ago gave
the green light to counterinsurgency by the army".
</P>
<P>
Paramilitaries mercilessly killed 45 men, women and children
who gathered at a church Monday in the village of Acteal, Chiapas
state.
</P>
<P>
Some witnesses said the killers were two dozen gunmen from the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI). However, the PRI
leaders denounced the killings, insisting they had no connection
with them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Zedillo bitterly condemned the massacre
while Interior Minister Emilio Chuayffet denied that the
government should bear any responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Jorge Madrazo, who was ordered to take over
the investigation, said that nine people in connection with the
Acteal massacre had been detained while more would be arrested
soon.
</P>
<P>
Both Zedillo and Chuayffet called for the renewal of the peace
talks between the government and the Zapatista rebels to end the
four-year-old war in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
The Zapatista guerrillas declared war on the government on
January 1, 1994, in a bid to obtain greater indigenous rights for
the Indian community.
</P>
<P>
The Monday massacre has triggered worldwide condemnations from
senior figures like United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
United States President Bill Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
