<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects Bright for Ukraine's Space Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Prospects of Ukraine's space
industry have been bright in recent years, said Valery Komarov, of
the Ukrainian National Space Agency (UNSA), on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Komarov, a deputy director of the space agency, said Ukrainian
astronaut Leonid Kadeniuk's latest flight aboard a U.S. space
shuttle was a proof of Ukraine's aerospace science.
</P>
<P>
Through international cooperation, he said, the UNSA is gaining
fame and cash.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the space industry earned 105 million U.S. dollars
from 115 foreign commercial agreements. And in the first eight
months of 1997, it earned 82.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
If talks succeed with Russia and the United States on joining
the Alpha program to build an international space station, Ukraine
will be among the world's top space nations, Komarov said.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic also joins Globalstar, a space-based
international communications project, and Sea Launch, a commercial
satellite launching project. Both projects look very promising.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is building a central control station in Crimea for
Globalstar, after winning, through bidding procedure, the contract
to launch 36 of the 48 satellites for the Globalstar system.
</P>
<P>
The use of Ukraine's Zenit rockets for Sea Launch will allow
the space industry to run at full capacity for two years. In the
initial stage, six to eight rockets will be launched annually.
</P>
<P>
Komarov expressed hope to export satellites, adding that
Ukraine is currently working on Sich-1M, a mini-satellite, and
plans to offer the technology to other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Russian Diplomacy in Face of NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the fall, Russia moved to develop relations with other big
European powers, strengthen its status as a "big power of Europe"
and reduce the U.S. influence in the European business.
</P>
<P>
Russia formed the "Big Europe" concept stressing that the
security of Europe should be protected, not by any foreign
intervenors, but the Europeans themselves.
</P>
<P>
This season also witnessed the frequent visits to Moscow by
leaders from major European countries. And most noticeable, Russia
started a special cooperative relationship with France and
Germany, and the three announced to hold regular summit every year.
</P>
<P>
Another move Russia took to create a better international
environment for itself in face of NATO expansion was to actively
develop relations with China, Japan, India, South Korea and the
Association of Southeast Asia Nations (ASEAN) including Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Russia regards the development of its friendly and
good-neighborly relations with China as a "separate priority area"
in its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Chinese President Jiang Zemin held two summit
meetings in 1997 and signed two joint communiques as well as a
series of documents.
</P>
<P>
Their meetings and the documents they signed injected new
vitality and substances into the 21st century-oriented
Russia-China strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
The "breakthrough" in Russia-Japan relations was another major
achievement in Russia's diplomacy in the Asian and Pacific region
this year.
</P>
<P>
In November, Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto held a two-day informal summit in Russia's Siberian city
of Krasnoyarsk and agreed on a plan designed to strengthen trade
and economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Hashimoto also committed to conclude a bilateral
peace treaty by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Russia's entrance into the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation at
its Vancouver informal leadership meeting last month paved the way
for Russia to fully undertake the Asian and Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
As part of its all-round foreign policy, Moscow put forward a
12-point program for realizing a comprehensive and just peace in
the Middle East and helped ease the latest tension between Iraq
and the United States over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov also made shuttle
visits to Latin America in November, aiming to enhance cooperation
with countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Although Russia's diplomacy in 1997 has achieved some positive
results, the containment and counter-containment struggle between
Moscow and NATO will go down well into the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hostage Taker Surrenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The fired postal worker who
held seven people hostage at a regional mail center in Denver
surrendered on Christmas Eve after a nine and a half hour standoff
with police.
</P>
<P>
Davis Lee Jackson, 42, surrendered at about 5:00 p.m. local
time (19:00 EST). The hostages were released unharmed, reports
from Denver said.
</P>
<P>
Jackson allegedly got into the building shortly after 7:00
a.m. local time with a shotgun, possibly through loading docks and
held the hostages in a supervisor's office in the mail sorting
building, police said.
</P>
<P>
The 24-hour mail center is one of the nation's largest and
busiest, handling most of the mail for Colorado and Wyoming. About
3,000 people work at the center, which includes a 24-hour post
office.
</P>
<P>
About 50 police officers and 25 Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI) agents surrounded the building during the standoff and
evacuated hundreds of workers.
</P>
<P>
Police negotiated with the gunman through the day and sent food
into the office.
</P>
<P>
The motivation was not immediately known, but the gunman was
fired for threatening a supervisor 18 months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
