<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Opposed to Selling Key Industry Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Minister of Fuel and
Power, Sergei Kiriyenko, told a press conference Wednesday that he
strongly opposed selling the stocks of key state-owned enterprises
which should be controlled by national majority shares, such as
Gas Monopoly-Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko signed a contract to manage the state stocks of the
Gas Monopoly-Gazprom on behalf of the national representative
committee of this company with its Board of Directors on December
20, so strengthening state control of this enterprise.
</P>
<P>
But it was reported that Russia's State Property Department
proposed, on December 23, that due to the large quantity and
difficult management of national assets, most state shares in
companies not dominantly state-owned, should be listed on the
market.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that state stocks in electric power,
transportation, fuel and gas and some other strategic products'
enterprises should be sold out first.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kiriyenko said Russia would make up a clear
investment method next year so as to actively attract more
overseas investors and protect their rights and interests. On the
other hand, foreign investors should obey Russian law when
operating businesses.
</P>
<P>
He said that only when the electric power become a product in
which the payments could be guaranteed could foreign capital flow
to the Russian power department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
