<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Province Launches Survey on Folk Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province, inhabited by 26 ethnic groups, has launched a survey on
its folk arts to save some endangered folk arts.
</P>
<P>
The survey, to be completed by September of 1998, will cover
dresses of different ethnic groups, ways and materials for making
various handicrafts, contents of artistic works, as well as folk
artisans.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, a group of folk artisans who have
special skills will be rewarded and named as "folk artists".
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minority groups account for one-third of the province's
total population. These ethnic groups has their own unique dresses
and produce colorful artistic products such as carvings, murals,
paper cut, prints, lacquer and bamboo instruments.
</P>
<P>
To promote its folk arts, the province has organized a group of
folk arts exhibitions and published books on folk arts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
