<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Projects in Chinese Province Attract More Overseas Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investors have
increasingly concentrated their attention on the large projects in
south China's land-locked province of Hunan.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the province had 145 overseas-funded
projects, with more than one million US dollars each, during the
first 11 months of this year. And altogether, 650 million US
dollars were actually used, accounting for 81 percent of the
province's total.
</P>
<P>
Of the 145 projects, 28 had a total investment of 423 million
US dollars, accounting for 52 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
To date, some large transnational companies, such as Hitachi
and Kobe Steel Corporation of Japan and LG of the Republic of
Korea, have gradually made their investment in the province.
</P>
<P>
Before 1992, overseas funds in Hunan were mainly from Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, which accounted to over 87 percent of the
province's total. And most of the investors were small and
medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
To attract more overseas investment, the provincial government
in 1993 established a department in charge of absorbing overseas
investment and offering a series of services for overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province sponsored four trade fairs during
1994-97. Now, the investment from foreign countries has almost
equaled that from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
