<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Peace at Last, Central America Seeks Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Leaving decades of civil wars
behind them, Central American countries have furthered on their
path towards peace and development in year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the five countries in the region, Guatemala was the last, in
1996, to see the ending of its internal armed conflict, following
the suits of Nicaragua in 1990 and of El Salvador in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, in 1997, at their leaders' four routine summit
meetings with counterparts from Honduras and Costa Rica, regional
cooperation, mainly economic, turned a new focus for discussions.
</P>
<P>
What they agreed on at the gatherings are the needs to
consolidate peace and democracy, step up reconstruction efforts,
carry out economic reforms, and accelerate the integration process.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting in May to "Bridge Toward the 21st Central," they
said Central America should take the opportunity provided by the
period of unprecedented stability and eradicate remnants of war.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, the Nicaraguan, Salvadoran and Guatemalan
governments pushed forwards their dialogues with the opposition,
and successfully persuaded most guerrilla groups to lay down arms.
</P>
<P>
In El Salvador, the government's "Gun for Food" program
proceeded well to allow civilians to hand in weapons in exchange
for food, so as to eliminate potential threat of civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
And in Honduras, the police force cut off its links with the
military and accepted the leadership of a civilian government
under a reform program.
</P>
<P>
Also through peaceful dialogues, Central American nations
resolved some of the disputes among themselves in 1997.
</P>
<P>
El Salvador and Honduras, once in war over border disputes,
improved their ties; and Nicaragua and Honduras sought diplomatic
means to decide their territorial waters available for fishing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nicaragua and Costa Rica, through consultations,
resolved the issue arising from the fact that thousands of
Nicaraguan laborers were staying and working in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Economically, years of armed conflicts have made Central
America the poorest region in Latin America, with 60 percent of
its 30 million population live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
But with the return of peace, the region's stagnant economy has
shown signs of recovery. Its economy grew by an average of 2.3
percent in 1996, and by an estimated 4.0 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Internally, by refocusing on economic development in the year,
Central American countries took a series of measures to adjust
economic structures, promote agriculture and diversify exports.
</P>
<P>
They also made efforts to boost international tourism and make
it a major foreign currency earner. As a result, tourism in the
region currently grows at an average annual rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
To attract more visitors, at least within the region,
Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua decided in November
to eliminate visa requirements on reciprocal basis.
</P>
<P>
On foreign trade, Central American countries are gradually
decreasing their dependence on the United States and expanding
cooperation with other countries and regions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Faced up with globalization and increasingly fierce competition
at the world market, Central American leaders have realized the
importance of joining hands, economically and politically, to
uplift the region's overall status in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In July, at a summit meeting in Panama City, they pledged to
speed up the regional integration process and give stronger
mandates to the Central American Parliament and Court.
</P>
<P>
Two months later, in Managua, Nicaragua, they agreed to
establish a regional political and economic union, and urged
Central Americans to give full support to create a "common house."
</P>
<P>
The process was substantiated in early 1997, with the erection
of a high-voltage power line to help alleviate power shortage in
the region between Guatemala in the north and Panama in the south.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed to raise 620 million U.S. dollars for
renovating the Central America section of the Pan-American
Highway. In addition, Honduras, El Salvador and Nicaragua agreed
to build a road linking the Pacific and Atlantic coasts.
</P>
<P>
As the momentum for continued growth is there at the end of the
year, Central American countries still face problems -- political,
economic and social -- left over by years of civil wars.
</P>
<P>
It's a consensus among analysts that a lot more, often harder,
work is needed to secure Central America's long-term social
stability and initiate the region's economic takeoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
