<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Russian Diplomacy in Face of NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 is a busy year
for Russian diplomacy. On the NATO east expansion issue, Russia
has conducted tough talks with the military alliance with an aim
to minimize the expansion's adverse impact.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Russia has enhanced cooperation among the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and improved its
relations with other European countries and Asian and Latin
American nations as well.
</P>
<P>
NATO's expansion to include former Warsaw Pact countries in
central and eastern Europe has been one of the major issues on
which Russia and the West had contradictory views since the end of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Russia views the move as part of the overall strategy of the
West of containing Russia and filling up the post-Cold War vacuum
in central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russian-U.S. relations became strained because the United
States pushed ahead with the NATO expansion. However, after the
first-stage expansion plan was announced, both sides took some
steps to improve their ties.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton invited his Russian counterpart
Boris Yeltsin to "fully" participate in the summit of the G-7
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia, on the other hand, adopted a pragmatic attitude toward
the United States in order to get more economic benefits from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the impossibility of preventing the NATO expansion,
Russia chose to minimize its effect on Russia's security interest
by striking a deal with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
After difficult bargains, President Yeltsin and the leaders of
NATO countries signed a historic document on the basic relations
between Russia and the military alliance on May 27.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed on a mechanism for future cooperation and
agreed to start a new-type cooperative relationship between them.
</P>
<P>
But the signing of the document did not lead to a solution of
the fundamental contradictions on the issue of NATO expansion
which Russia still considers a "strategic mistake" the West made
after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
To prevent NATO expansion from reaching its borders, Russia was
firmly opposed to NATO accepting Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania as
its new members, and went as far as to offer security cover to the
three Baltic countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also announced that Russia will cut by 40 percent its
army and naval forces stationed in the northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
As another safeguard against NATO expansion, Russia made great
efforts to improve its relations with other CIS members and
promoted CIS integration more vigorously. Russia and Belarus
upgraded the Community of Sovereign Republics, formed by them only
in April 1, to a Union, to speed up their economic and political
integration.
</P>
<P>
In May, Yeltsin made his state visit to Ukraine, the first of
its kind since the Soviet Union's disintegration in 1991, and
achieved a breakthrough in the bilateral relations. In Kiev,
Yeltsin and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma signed the Treaty of
Friendship, Cooperation and Partnership and put an end to the
long-standing problem of the Black Sea fleet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
