<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: EU-China Ties Make Apparent Progress in 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union-China ties
in politics, trade and investment have scored eye-catching
progress in 1997, according to a leading EU official in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, ambassador Endymion
Wilkinson, head of the delegation of the EU European Commission,
especially mentioned the new strategy toward China approved by the
commission in November of 1996, which stressed its "overall,
independent and long-range" features.
</P>
<P>
According to the new strategy, the EU would further promote
exchanges and cooperation in economy, trade, science, technology
and development assistance with China.
</P>
<P>
Wilkinson said that last year's EU-China high-level exchange of
visits was more frequent, while both sides cooperated very well in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the ambassador, in the first Europe-Asia summit
held in Bangkok in March of 1996, China played a "very positive
role" and leaders of the EU nations are looking forward to meeting
Chinese leaders in the second Europe-Asia summit scheduled for
next April in London.
</P>
<P>
China has also undertaken frequent and positive dialogues with
the EU on China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO),
making great progress, Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
He said vice-president Leon Brittan of the EU Commission had
very fruitful talks in October with Chinese Minister Wu Yi of the
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, in which both sides
reached consensus on some issues of principle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: EU-China Ties Make Apparent Progress in 1997 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, he went on to say, the EU-China negotiations on
China's entry into the WTO have entered an important period and
both sides are undertaking positive dialogues.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador added that EU-China trade has been on rise and
EU practical investment in China has also maintained its upward
momentum.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission recently decided to propose removing the
"non-market economy" label applied to China in the EU's
anti-dumping policy, he said, adding that this indicates the EU
has recognized China's ongoing reform is moving toward a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The EU is still one of the best high-technology suppliers to
China and, in 1997, the EU assistance fund for China's cooperation
projects has amounted to 65-to-70 million ECU (about 72 to 84
million U.S. dollars), three times that of 1994, Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, the EU and China have 30 cooperation
projects and have signed agreements on many new projects.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 the EU assistance fund for cooperative projects with
China will remain at the same level as this year, the ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
Also next year, he said, many leaders of EU nations will be
visiting China. He said he expects EU-China political relations to
improve, while bilateral trade and investment will continue to
increase.
</P>
<P>
"Bilateral talks on China's entry into the WTO will gain more
progress," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
