<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Crisis to Reduce Demand for Chinese Rolled Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in
Southeast Asia will reduce China's rolled steel exports and make
China's domestic market more competitive next year, according to a
report in the latest issue of China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
The report said that less demand from Southeast Asia, a major
overseas market for China's rolled steel, will severely affect
China's exports.
</P>
<P>
"The Asia-Pacific region will see its need for rolled steel
decrease by 20 percent," said the newspaper, sponsored by the
development and research center of the State Council. "In areas
severely affected by the crisis, such as Thailand, most
construction sites have been halted and some car manufacturers
will cease production for a few months."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's domestic market will face stiff competition
from Southeast Asian countries, whose products will become cheaper
and more competitive following the depreciation of their
currencies, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
China's tendency to further lower its tariff from its October
cut to 10 percent in 2005, a level lower than average for
developing countries, means China is likely to encounter stronger
pressure for imports, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper estimates that imports of rolled steel from other
Southeast Asian nations will be higher in 1998 because of their
currency depreciation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
