<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Sue Anderlecht Over Bribery Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- English first division side
Nottingham Forest and 16 former players have started court action
against Belgian club Anderlecht over the 1984 UEFA Cup bribery
scandal.
</P>
<P>
Forest's Belgian lawyer Filip Goemans said on Wednesday that a
writ had been served against former Andrlecht chairman Constant
Vanden Stock and Raymond van Deken for their failure to respond
whithin a three month deadline.
</P>
<P>
Vanden Stock admitted in September that he paid 27,000 US
dollars as a "loan" to the Spanish referee in the second leg of
the 1984 UEFA Cup semifinal which they won 3-0 and reached the
final 3-2 on aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Forest, who had won the first leg 2-0, controversially
disallowed a goal in the return leg.
</P>
<P>
Goemans said Forest had tried for three months to reach a
financial settlement and received no positive reaction from
Anderlecht.
</P>
<P>
Forest and their players are seeking up to seven million US
dollars in damages from Anderlecht and the two club officials.
</P>
<P>
The case is seen as an embarrasment for the Belgian soccer
union and they are under pressure to end the dispute before the
2000 European Nations Championships being jointly-hosted by
Belgium and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Goemans said a financial agreement was still possible and would
benefit the game's credibility.
</P>
<P>
In September, Anderlecht were banned by UEFA from playing in
the next European competition for which they qualify. 
</P>
</TEXT>
