<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Seeking IMF Loan to Aid Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank is
seeking a two billion U.S. dollar short-term loan from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to aid its foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports Thursday, the new loan, which
will fall under a so-called precautionary arrangement, will last
for 12 to 18 months although it is still under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying that
the IMF "will come here, assuming we complete the (existing
program) on the latter part of January to talk about the
precautionary arrangement."
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was to have exited 35 years of IMF tutelage at
the end of this month, but the IMF has deferred its final review
on ending the program to see whether the country meets two
requirements -- passage of a new oil-deregulation law and posting
a budget surplus in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On a "very, very preliminary basis", Singson said, talks are
also going on between the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank to provide "program loans" to the country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said it was a step toward restoring confidence and
easing pressure on the Philippine peso, which has lost one third
of its value since July 11.
</P>
<P>
They said it is important that at least half of the two billion
dollars will be disbursed quickly so rising fears about the health
of the country's foreign reserves and the stability of the local
currency can be addressed immediately.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign reserves stood at just below 10 billion
dollars last week, less than three months' worth of imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
