<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 25 (Xinhua) -- An upgrading of technology at
the Guizhou Moutai Distillery Group is expected to increase
productivity by 50 percent when completed in 2000. The project at
the distillery in southwestern China's Guizhou Province will cost
400 million yuan (nearly 50 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The annual production capacity of the group is 4,000 tons of
moutai, a liquor made from sorghum grain. This was achieved after
the completion of two upgrades in recent years for an investment
of 530 million yuan (about 55 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The group expects to make an historic record by turning out
4,400 tons of moutai this year while earning 500 million yuan in
sales, said Ji Keliang, chairman of the group's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
The new project that will become operational in 2000 will raise
the annual production capacity to 6,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The production of moutai, one of the most popular spirits in
the world along with French cognac and Scottish whisky, is
restricted by complicated and time-consuming workmanship.
</P>
