<HEADLINE> Air New Zealand Suspends Flights to Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Air New Zealand has
announced it suspends indefinitely all its four weekly flights to
Seoul as the South Korean financial crisis has hit all sectors of
New Zealand's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The airlines said the South Korean market has "evaporated" in
the wake of the crisis, TVNZ reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said the South Korean currency won has devaluated
drastically, and there are now few passengers flying out of South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The decision followed a report that the number of South Korean
tourists to New Zealand has fallen 90 percent following the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Board deputy chief executive Chris Ryan said he was
still optimistic about the long-term future of the South Korean
market, but it is going to take time to re-build.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 25 travel companies met in Auckland Wednesday to
discuss the serious situation they are now facing, as the number
of tourists from many other Asian countries is also down.
</P>
<P>
Some tour operators said if the situation continues, they will
have to sell their tourist buses to quit the business.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the fasting growing market for New Zealand's
tourism industry in the past few years. Before the crisis, the
number of tourists from that country grew at over 40 percent
annually to top 110,000.  
</P>
