<HEADLINE> Price Stable on Shanghai's Non-Staple Food Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The non-staple food market in
Shanghai, China's largest commercial center, has remained stable,
after the city lifted the control of prices for eggs and meat on
the market last July.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has also cancelled all the subsidies granted to the
production and trade of meat and eggs in a bid to push
producers and traders into the market.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices for fresh pork and eggs had been remained 15
yuan (1.8 U.S. dollars) and 5.98 yuan (0.7 U.S. dollars) per kg
during the January-October period. Even when No.11 typhoon stroke
the city in November, the prices had not fluctuated by a large
margin.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as a result of a fiercer market competition, more
varieties of fresher meat and egg products are presented on stalls
to diversify people's dining table.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has a total of 722 breeding farms in the suburbs,
which supply 30 to 50 percent of the city's meat and eggs. It will
invest in large production bases outside the city. 
</P>
