<HEADLINE> Saved Crane Finds New Home in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A red-crowned crane, rescued
from a butcher's knife by a resident in Hebei Province, has been
given a new home, safe and comfortable, at the Tianjin Zoo.
</P>
<P>
Chen Baobin, a member of the Huanghua City Committee of Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference of Hebei Province,
happened to find the rare animal on sale at a free market for
butcher's meat and poultry early last month, said today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Seeing that the "big bird" was quite different from other local
poultry, Chen suspected it might be a rare animal under State
protection.
</P>
<P>
He bought the "big bird" at a cost of 500 yuan (US 60.2
dollars) and took it home.
</P>
<P>
The bird has a big appetite -- it eats more than three
kilograms of live fish each day. Chen fed the bird at his own cost.
</P>
<P>
After ten days of talking via telephone with various
authorities, he finally got in touch with Tianjin Zoo.
</P>
<P>
The zoo immediately sent an expert to Chen's home to help
assess the value of the bird.
</P>
<P>
According to the expert, Lu Baoquan, the bird is a re-crowned
crane, a rare animal under first-class State protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
