<HEADLINE> Shanghainese Prefer Securities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 42 percent of the respondents said they would purchase stocks
and bonds following the bank interest rate cut on October 23, a
rise of 31 percent compared to the previous survey.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-nine percent said they would withdraw savings to
purchase consumer goods, and only 29 percent said they would keep
their bank savings account, down significantly from the 43 percent
on the previous survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that local residents have a variety of
reasons for saving money, ranging from saving for unexpected daily
expenses to paying for their child's education expenses and
marriage costs, and purchasing expensive commodities.
</P>
<P>
An in-depth analysis revealed that 38.3 percent of respondents
prefer current deposits, compared to more than 80 percent who
formerly preferred fixed deposits.
</P>
<P>
Some 30.3 percent of respondents noted declines in their income
levels, up 6.6 percent on the previous survey, and 76.6 percent
expressed optimism concerning the inflation level.  
</P>
