<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Ten International Sports Stories of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Following are the top ten
international sports stories of 1997 selected by the Sports News
Service of the Xinhua News Agency:
</P>
<P>
1. Greek capital Athens was awarded the right to host the 28th
Olympic Games. The Games will return to its birth-place in 2004
after 108 years.
</P>
<P>
2. Chinese badminton team reinstated their leading position in
the world after winning 15 titles in major tournaments.
</P>
<P>
3. A total of 32 teams qualified for the World Cup finals in
France next year after 643 matches in two years with South Africa,
Croatia, Japan and Jamaica making their debuts and Asia having four
entries for the first time in the elite tournament.
</P>
<P>
4. Chinese women's runners once again proved their strength in
the middle and long distance events when Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei
broke the 5,000 meters world record at the Eighth National Games.
Now the Chinese hold four world records in middle and
long-distance races.
</P>
<P>
5. Young generation appeared in the tennis world when Martina
Hingis replaced Steffi Graf to take the top spot in the WTA
rankings. Pete Sampras dominated the men's field, but he was
challenged by the youths.
</P>
<P>
6. Mike Tyson was banned from boxing indefinitely after his
disgusting ear-biting performance in a WBA heavyweight title bout
against Evander Holyfield in Las Vegas in June.
</P>
<P>
7. China led the team standings by collecting eight golds among
25 medal winners at the Fourth World Wushu Championships which
attracted 60 entries. The International Wushu Federation now has
78 member associations.
</P>
<P>
8. Deep Blue, a supercomputer of IBM, defeated Garry Kasparov
in a six-game series in May, creating a record that for the first
time in history a program beat reigning a world chess champion.
</P>
<P>
9. Juan Antonio Samaranch was re-elected president of the
International Olympic Committee at the 106th IOC session. The
session also elected American Anita Defrantz as IOC's first woman
vice-president.
</P>
<P>
10. Track and field legend Carl Lewis of the United States
retired at the age of 35 after winning nine Olympic gold medals
and eight world championship titles in his career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997: Bumper Harvest for Chinese Badminton (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Manifested by the successes
at the key events, the year of 1997 saw a renaissance of China in
the sport of badminton.
</P>
<P>
After hitting nadir in the past years, the Chinese shuttlers
staged a dramatic comeback masterminded by headcoach Li Yongbo.
</P>
<P>
Just as the former world champion put it, "It is the overall
strength and supriority of our players that bring us many
victories."
</P>
<P>
The strength is formidable and the supriority obvious.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese started by pocketing four of the five golds at
stake in March's All England Open and celebrated a bountiful Year
of Ox by repeating the feat at the year-ending World Grand Prix
Finals in Jakarta in December, with only the men's doubles
eluding them in both.
</P>
<P>
They made a big bag of trophies at the World Championships in
Scotland in May, where the mixed team Sudirman Cup is retained in
the Chinese hands and three individual crowns were captured.
</P>
<P>
Had Sun Jun not been forced to withdraw by injuries in the
final, he might have taken the fourth in the men's singles, where
the Danish doctor Peter Rasmussen triumphed eventually.
</P>
<P>
Sun, however, was consoled by winning his first ever world
title at the World Cup and routing his fellow countryman and All
England champion Dong Jiong in the Grand Prix finals.
</P>
<P>
Former world number one Dong hit jinx this year. He saw his
form scratching bottom after a high fever forced him to retire
from the third round at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Dong even failed to grab a finals berth at the National Games
last October and was stopped by Indonesia's Alan Budi Kusuma in
the third round of the U.S. Open in September.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen, who won his only other international title in
January in Japan, produced far less impressive performances after
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
He was dumped in the second round of the Danish Open, bowed
out of the third round in the U.S. Open and was eliminated in the
group competition in the World Grand Prix finals.
</P>
<P>
Although the Chinese men took almost all the larger events,
another Dane Peter-Gade Christensen soared to the top slot on the
world rankings with victories in Chinese Taipei and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He was also the finalist at the Malaysian Open and the
U.S. Open, and the semi-finalist at Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
