<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997: Bumper Harvest for Chinese Badminton (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An awesome squad of Chinese women's singles players, led by
world number two Ye Zhaoying and teenager Gong Zhichao, flexed
their muscles as the Indonesians waned.
</P>
<P>
Their power was highlighted at the World Championships with
unprecedented all-Chinese semi-finals after Gong forced
Indonesian legend Susi Susanti to sign off what could be her last
championships in a losing note.
</P>
<P>
Ye almost took a clean sweep of all the major events this
year, beating Gong to win the All England Open and the World
Championships and Susanti for Grand Prix overall title.
</P>
<P>
Susanti added just another World Cup to her trophy room by
defeating Gong and Ye on her way to the top of the podium.
</P>
<P>
Mia Audina, hailed as her heir-apparent, managed to win her
only title at the Konica Open in Singapore, predicting a much
weakened Indonesia camp after the imminent retirement of Susanti.
</P>
<P>
Possibly the best all-round doubles player ever in the world,
the reticent 21-year-old Ge Fei is the key to half of the Chinese
triumph.
</P>
<P>
She teamed up with Gu Jun to set the standard for any shuttler
when they completed an enviable "Grand Slam" of the Olympic,
World Championships, All England, World Grand Prix Finals and the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
After the retirement of Gil Young Ah, half of South Korea's
former world champion pair, the level of Ge and Gu is so beyond
the reach of any other pairs that they won every event entered.
</P>
<P>
Ge's mixed doubles partnership with Liu Yong, which began in
November 1996, also produced stunning fruit of victories.
</P>
<P>
The men's doubles is still the Indonesian territory. Claiming
two star duos of Ricky Subagja and Rexy Mainaky, and Candra
Wijaya and Budiarto Sigit, the Indonesians won almost all the
major trophies.
</P>
<P>
Wijaya and Sigit triumphed at World Grand Prix Finals and the
World Championships while Subagja and Mainaky took the World Cup,
which was the last edition.
</P>
<P>
But they have to watch out for the rising South Korean pair
Lee Dong Soo and Yoo Yong Sung, runners-up to either Indonesian
duo in many events.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesians pulled their biggest haul at home, where they
had a clean sweep of the titles with the Chinese absent in the
Indonesian Open.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese squad, which originally planned to compete in the
event, evoked controversy by pulling out en mass citing the late
issuing of some players' visas as the main reason.
</P>
<P>
In a move to better promote the world's fastest racket sport,
the International Badminton Confederation (IBF) decided in May to
scrap the World Cup and replace it with so-called "spectaculars".
</P>
<P>
Their focus will on areas out of Asia and the Nordic nations,
such as the American continents and the Oceania.
</P>
<P>
The IBF also disclosed in December that a "SuperSeries"
tournaments, which include the upgraded key Grand Prix events, is
to kick off in 1999 to provide a "distinctive presentational
approach". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
