<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Making Northeastern Chinese City's Traffic More Orderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Drivers roll on the main
streets of Dalian in northeast China's Liaoning Province may now
encounter fewer red lights if they keep their speed above 30 kmph.
</P>
<P>
The city's traffic lights at 110 intersections are now
controlled by a traffic computer system that has proven effective
in regulating traffic flow on major thoroughfares. It has saved at
least 50 million yuan (six million U.S. dollars) in fewer traffic
jams, accidents, and energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is northeastern China's largest port and is known as one
of the country's fastest growing economies. It has a population of
2.6 million, and 240,000 automobiles and is growing at 20 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
However, because of the city government's placing importance on
urban planning and traffic controls, traffic snarls haven't been
the problem they have in most large cities.
</P>
<P>
The city's 31 one-way streets have an average speed-limit of 40
kmph and most two-way streets have speeds above 30 kmph, as
opposed to 15 kmph in other large cities.
</P>
<P>
The 44 million-yuan computer system has 10 sub-systems, and
uses state-of-the-art technology from Britain and Canada.
</P>
<P>
On a 40-sq.m. lighted signal board in the Public Security
Bureau's traffic control center, traffic police can monitor
traffic conditions on an approximately 100-sq.km. urban area
provided by sixty video monitors installed on major
thoroughfares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
