<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Fourth American Adults Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government said
today that adult smokers represented nearly 25 percent of their
same age group in the United States in 1995 and it would be hard
to meet its goal of 15 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
(CDC) said 24.7 percent of the nation's adults, or 47 million
people, were smokers in 1995, down only slightly from 24.8 percent
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Among the smokers, 24.5 million were men and 22.4 million were
women. Those who had not graduated from high school and those
living below the poverty level were the heaviest smokers, CDC
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency said 70 percent of the smokers promised to
give up the habit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
