<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Firms Agree to Pay Investors Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Thirty of Wall Street's
biggest firms agreed to pay investors 910 million U.S. dollars to
settle a lawsuit alleging that they overcharged clients in the
Nasdaq Stock Market, lawyers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal is the largest civil antitrust settlement in history,
according to the lawyers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
The settlement follows government action to discipline the big
trading firms for keeping stock prices artificially high, a
practice that investigators said increased company profits and
raised costs for investors.
</P>
<P>
Investors said that between 1989 and 1994 the company's
securities dealers purposely kept the gap between prices for
buying and selling a stock artificially wide. That made trades
more expensive for investors.
</P>
<P>
The biggest names in securities trading -- J.P. Morgan
Securities Inc., Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Smith Barney Inc. and
PaineWebber Inc., among others -- will share in the cost of paying
several million investors, who include major market players and
huge mutual fund companies.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for investors had reached six earlier settlements
totaling 100 million U.S. dollars, bringing to 1 billion U.S.
dollars the amount of cash that will be distributed to investors
who overpaid for trades as a result of the dealers' pricing
practices.
</P>
<P>
The agreements must be approved by U.S. District Judge Robert
Sweet in Washington. A hearing has been set for December 29.
</P>
<P>
The settlement comes 18 months after the Justice Department
settled its own antitrust suit against 24 companies. The
department said that Nasdaq dealers engaged in a widespread
practice of quoting stock prices by rounding off prices to the
nearest quarter of a dollar.
</P>
<P>
The settlement didn't involve any criminal charges or fines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Government Spends 1.38 Billion US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Emergency
Management Agency (FEWA)said today that it spent more than 1.38
billion U.S. dollars this year to aid communities hit by violent
storms, tornadoes and floods.
</P>
<P>
FEMA Director James Lee Witt said in a statement that the Red
River Valley floods that hit Minnesota and the Dakotas in early
April, severe winter storms that hit western states in January and
flooding in the Ohio River Valley in March were the most costly
disasters on which the agency spent more than one billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agency said, disasters were declared in 27 states and three
western Pacific island territories in 1997. It provided housing
assistance worth 319.4 million dollars to 127,064 disaster victims,
100 million dollars in grants for transportation, medical and
other needs for nearly 50,000 victims.
</P>
<P>
Minnesota and Washington state led the nation in need for
disaster assistance in the year, and U.S. President Bill Clinton
declared four disasters in each state in response to severe winter
storms and Spring and Summer floods.
</P>
<P>
The president declared more than one disaster in other six
states, three for South Dakota and two each for Arkansas, Idaho,
Illinois, North Dakota and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
The agency said it spent 1.7 billion dollars on disasters aid
in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
