<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Stocks Slip Into Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street edged
lower Wednesday in a shortened Christmas Eve session, with the
Nasdaq market index dropping below 1,500 for the first time since
July.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average jumped out to a 48-point gain
in early trading, but quickly pulled back and fell 31.64 points to
7,660.13 by the early close, trimming its gain for 1997 to 18.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indicators also turned lower.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 10.38 to 1,499.53. While still
up 16 percent this year, the index has slid more than 14 percent
from its peak at 1,745.85 on October 9.
</P>
<P>
Although another steep drop in South Korean stock prices
threatened to extend Tuesday's damage on Wall Street, Japanese and
other foreign markets held steady Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. markets are scheduled to shut down early for Christmas
Eve, stay closed on Thursday for Christmas, and then hold another
shortened session on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled just 263.31
million shares at the 1 p.m. closing bell, down from 293.20 million
at the same point on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 6.43 to 932.70, and
the NYSE composite index fell 2.53 to 492.32, but the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.07 to 662.60.
</P>
<P>
Stocks drew some pressure from the bond market, where interest
rates rose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
