<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Russia to Launch Joint Space Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 24 (Xinhua) -- France and Russia will launch a
joint space mission from January 29 to February 19, 1998, in which
four Russian astronauts and one French cosmonaut will jointly work
on the space station Mir.
</P>
<P>
The National Center of Space Studies of France said today that
French cosmonaut Leopold Eyharts will join Russian astronauts
Talgat Mossabayev and Nicolai Boudarine on board a Soyuz-TM-27
space craft to take off from the cosmodrome of Baikonour in
Kazakhstan on January 29 at 21:33 local time (17:33 Paris time).
</P>
<P>
They will arrive at the Mir space station at 19:33 Paris time
to begin the Pegase space mission whose objective is to complete
the experiments on life sciences, physical sciences and
technologies which were begun in September 1996 by French
spacewoman Claudie Andre-Deshays on the Mir station.
</P>
<P>
Eyharts will return to Earth on February 19 at 14:17 (10:17
Paris time) with two Russian spacemen, Anatoli Slolviev and Pavel
Vinogradov, already having worked on the space station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
