<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy Grows Moderately in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy grew at an
annual rate of 4.2 percent in October, Statistics Canada reported
today.
</P>
<P>
On the month-to-month basis, the gross domestic product
expanded 0.2 percent in October, the same pace as in September,
the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Goods-producing industries gained 0.7 percent in the month,
while services-producing industries saw no growth as a result of
labor dispute in the country's largest province of Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Output in manufacturing rose 0.9 percent in October after
declining 0.4 percent in August and 0.1 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
Production increased in 19 of the 22 major groups, with
transportation equipment, foodstuffs, electrical and electronic
equipment, and metal products accounting for nearly 60 percent of
the gain.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, wholesaling activity rose 1.6 percent, as
sales increased in all trade groups, except for small declines in
sales of lumber and building materials, and farm machinery.
</P>
<P>
Retail rose 0.4 percent in October, the fourth consecutive
monthly increase, reflecting higher sales of motor vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
