<HEADLINE> Israel to Decide Second Redeployment Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today announced that if there is no terror
attacks against Israel during the period, his government can
decide on the further redeployment in the West Bank next month.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee of
the Knesset (parliament) that the government was now on the
process of working out the country's vital security interests
over the second pullback from the West bank and the decision
could be taken in January, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
But he added that a five-month waiting period would be
required before implementation of the decision in order to test
if the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) can fulfill its
commitment to fighting terrorism effectively.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the announcement after he and most of his
cabinet ministers Tuesday made a helicopter tour of the West Bank
areas that may be included in the next pullback in an effort to
consolidate a position on the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
And if the decision is taken on schedule, Netanyahu will
be able to show U.S. President Bill Clinton the precise scope
of the next withdrawal when they meet in Washington in
January.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also stressed that so far he has not given any
U.S. representatives the percentage about the pending pullback in
the West Bank. He contended that it was impossible because only
the cabinet could make such a decision.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition Labor leader Ehud Barak charged today that
Netanyahu bowed to U.S. pressures and made a secret deal with
Washington and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said that according to the deal, Netanyahu agreed to
give 10.5 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in
the second withdrawal, while the U.S. agreed that the Likud
government delayed its decision on the redeployment until
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
