<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today expressed
welcome to a United Nations resolution to extend the mandate of
the U.N. Peace Keeping Force in Cyprus to June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said the U.N. Security Council has considered European
Union's decision to start accession talks with Cyprus next March
as an important development in the efforts to solve the protracted
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that the resolution has mentioned the agreement on
missing people in Cyprus reached by Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash last July, which
he said is the first time that a relevant resolution touches
humanitarian issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council resolution adopted Tuesday stressed
the U.N. support for the efforts made by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan to help solve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed support for Annan's decision to resume
negotiations between the Greek Cypriots and the Turkish Cypriots
next March aimed at ending the division of the island.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peace-keeping force in Cyprus was established in 1964
to help stop violence that erupted after the breakup of a
government represented by both the Greek Cypriots and the Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 peacekeepers are patroling the 180-kilometer
dividing line across the country between the rival Greek Cypriots
and Turkish Cypriots. Their current mandate expires at the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an eastern Mediterranean island, has been divided since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third after a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been making efforts to help Cyprus reunite in a
formula of bizonal and bicommunal federation, but no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971225.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Trade Gap Widens Owing to Strong Pound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- British exports are finally
showing signs of suffering from the strength of sterling.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit widened from 1.25 billion pounds (2 billion
US dollars) to 1.32 billion pounds (2.11 billion US dollars) in
October, the biggest monthly gap recorded for two years, according
to the latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
Analysts blamed the strength of the pound for the fall in
exports and surge in imports in October, saying the figures
provided fresh evidence that the strength of sterling was slowly
eating into exports.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-1996, sterling has appreciated by about 20 percent
against other currencies, making imports to the UK cheaper and
goods sold abroad more expensive.
</P>
<P>
Details provided by the Office for National Statistics (ONS)
reveal that export volumes are still rising but the increase of
0.6 percent recorded over the past three months has been swamped
by news of a 2.5 percent leap in the volume of goods imported over
the same period.
</P>
<P>
However, the ONS said the trend was for the deficit to worsen
in coming months. It said that provisional estimates of trade
volumes outside the European Union showed exports down by 3
percent in November, and import volumes continuing to reach record
levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
