uncovered three days ago, a military spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Although some officers were arrested involving in the botched
coup plot, it did not indicate a division in the army, said Col.
Godwin Ugbo, acting director of defense information.
</P>
<P>
On the charge by the chief of army staff, Major-General
Ishaiya Bamaiyi to officers and men during the just-concluded
army conference in Enugu state, southeast Nigeria, on the need
for cohesion, Ugbo said the general only gave a fatherly advice
and not an indication of a division.
</P>
<P>
The defense spokesman also dismissed rumours that a key
officer in the presidency, Major Ali Mustapha, was killed in the
plot.
</P>
<P>
"Such a thing never happened. The officer is still alive," he
said.
</P>
<P>
As for any incident of more arrests or even the alleged
shooting during Sunday's arrest operation, Ugbo said he was yet
to clarify, noting that civilians could find it difficult to
differentiate a gun shot from any other sound.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government announced on Sunday the uncovering of
a coup plot, involving the country's number two person Lt.-Gen
Oladipo Diya, and 11 others who were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Investigations were still continuing, said Ugbo, who appealed
to journalists to "report only what you know". 
