<HEADLINE> Angola Reports Grain Deficit of 541,000 Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Angola in southern Africa will
suffer a grain deficit of 541,000 tons in 1997, its Agricultural
Minister Carlos Fernandes said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said on the state radio that Angola expected a
grain production of 441,000 tons in 1997, but the actual output
is only 431,000 tons, while the demand stands at 972,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes attributed the poor production to political turmoils
following the country's many years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimate of the Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations, Angola has a total arable
land of three million hectares, producing mainly yam, beans, corn
and sorghum.
</P>
<P>
Years of civil war, however, has turned the former grain
exporter country into a pure importer, with tens of thousands of
its population living on international aid. 
</P>
