<HEADLINE> Over 50,000 Nigerians Die at Child Birth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 24 (xinhua) -- More than 50,000 women have
died during child birth in Nigeria so far this year, with most of
deaths caused by the abandonment of them by their male
counterparts or family members.
</P>
<P>
The figure can be translated to 140 deaths daily or one death
every 10 minutes, the project directress of Mental Health
Rehabilitation Foundation, Bridget Juwah, said today in the
capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Other factors which facilitated the deaths were financial,
social and sometimes psychological, she said, quoted by the News
Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to her, maternal death could be reduced through the
redressing of the social inequalities confronting women and
ensuring that couples have access to family planning facilities.
</P>
<P>
She called for maternity care, back-up and support facilities
at the referral level, as well as offer of financial and
emotional support for abandoned pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
The project director also urged both the public and private
sectors to assist her foundation to stop "this endemic problem
that poses a threat to mankind".  
</P>
</TEXT>
