<HEADLINE> Gulf States Sign Protocol for Curbing Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Seven littoral states of the
Gulf signed a draft protocol here today in a bid to curb pollution
in the Gulf waters, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, the signatory states should draw up laws
and regulations to prevent dumping pollutants to the Gulf, the Sea
of Oman and the northern Indian Ocean, and curb entry of all forms
of wastes harmful to the environment.
</P>
<P>
The document called Tehran Protocol was signed at the end of a
three-day meeting of environmental experts and legal consultants
of the Regional Organization for Protecting Marine Environment
(ROPME), IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Except Iraq, ROPME's other members Iran, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman,
the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia signed the
protocol.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said that the protocol is a supplement of the Bazel
Convention signed by ROPME's members to provide ways and means of
better implementing the convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
