<HEADLINE> State Duma Fails to Approve 1998 Budget in Second </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, lower
house of Parliament, on Wednesday failed to approve in second
reading the federal budget bill for 1998, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
After three rounds of voting the document was short of just one
one vote to be passed. A total of 225 lawmakers voted for, while
226 voted against.
</P>
<P>
Numerous amendments were made to the draft in the course of
debate on the second reading. Speaker of the State Duma Gennady
Seleznyov said that the outcome was not politically motivated,
simply "a lot of amendments were turned down during the debate."
</P>
<P>
Acting chairman of the Budget Committee Alexander Zhukov said
the trilateral commission of the government and both houses of
parliament redistributed 27.9 billion redenominated rubles within
the budget, in particular by reducing subsidies to the social
insurance fund, appropriations for foreign activities and state
and local government administration costs.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chairman of the Duma's Communist Party faction Valentin
Kuptsov on Tuesday stated that the faction would vote against the
draft 1998 federal budget at the second-reading debate.
</P>
<P>
He said communists oppose the budget because it did nothing to
resolve the problem of disbursements to economic sectors. Besides,
regional members of the communist faction are dismayed by "problem
of a lack of protection of the social sphere and appropriation of
funds for science and education, and uncertainty with issues
related to the development budget".
</P>
<P>
The State Duma will vote again on Thursday. It is hard to
predict the results of the upcoming voting, Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 federal budget bill was approved in the first reading
by the State Duma on December 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
