<HEADLINE> Fresh Poll Shows Moi's Bigger Chance to Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The latest poll issued by a
non-governmental group here today said that Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi can get enough votes for his final five-year term
in Monday's general elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey of the Institute for Education in
Democracy (IED), although the number of his supporters appears to
be decreasing, Moi can still command a minimum 25 percent of the
vote in five of the country's eight provinces to assure his
victory.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted among 1,500 households across the
country, showed that Moi's popularity fell slightly from 40.8
percent in the first poll at the end of November to 40.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
"What it (the poll) tells you is that Moi is leading, but
there has been a change as a result of the two weeks of
campaigning," local sources quoted IED chief Grace Githu as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of Democratic Party's presidential candidate
Mwai Kibaki has risen from 13.7 percent to the 20.8 percent this
time.
</P>
<P>
Charity Ngilu, one of Kenya's first two women presidential
candidates, was maintaining her performance in Nairobi and Coast
Province and gained some ground in her home Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
Raila Odinga, who attracts the populous Luo vote in Nyanza
Province, has also gained significantly in Nairobi, scoring 12
percent from 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 people are on the top gear to vie for the
country's top seat, the crowdest race since Kenya declared
independence early 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
