<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned About Greece-PKK Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today voiced its
concern over Greece's links with Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said at a news
briefing that Turkey hopes the Greek government halts its support
for the PKK.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports today, a PKK member, Esref Kilic,
who has surrendered to the Turkish general consulate in Iranian
city of Urumiye, confessed that he has been trained in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the reports, the Turkish spokesman said that "if
he was really trained in Greece, it would once more prove the
Greek support for the PKK."
</P>
<P>
He added that this incident will be considered with other
similar cases.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Greece of supporting the PKK, a charge
denied by Greece.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war since 1984 against the Turkish
government for the establishment of an independent Kurdish state
in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Turkey and Greece have worsened due to
each other's expulsion of diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has announced to expel a Greek diplomat on charges of
spying for the PKK this week, and Greece kicked out a Turkish
diplomat in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over limits of air space and
the Aegean Sea, territorial disputes over some islands in the
Aegean Sea, rights to sea-bed minerals and the Cyprus
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
