<HEADLINE> China Supports Mideast Peace Process, Says FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen said today that China is willing to propel,
together with other members of the international community, the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark during his talks with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa at the Foreign Ministry premises after his
arrival here this morning.
</P>
<P>
"China supports the relevant United Nations resolutions and
fully agrees to the land-for-peace principle forged in the Madrid
peace conference (1991), and pointed up these view points to the
Israeli government on several occasions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Peace shall be the sole option for the Middle East" and a
deadlock in the peace process "will not do any good to any party,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Qian briefed Moussa on his Mideast tour that has taken him to
Lebanon, Syria, Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas, during
which he held profound discussions with various parties of the
region on means to promote the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"During the tour, I have a strong impression that the Mideast
peace process is blocked by artificial obstacles that must be
overcome," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said "the international community has the duty of working
with the various parties in the Mideast to realize a
comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
Moussa blamed the serious peace crisis in the Middle East on
the fact that the incumbent Israeli Likud government has "reversed
the policy and pledges of the former Israeli government," which
prompted deep concerns among countries in the Middle East and
world-wide.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the land-for-peace principle has been widely
accepted by the international community, Moussa said "the crux is
to restart the Palestinian-Israeli talks and make progress in the
regional cooperation and economic development."
</P>
<P>
He said that it is important for China in its capacity as a
permanent member of the U.N. Security Council to play a role in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Qian spoke highly of the initiator's role of Egypt in the
Mideast peace process, saying China appreciates Cairo's active
efforts and special role in boosting the peace process and Arab
unity.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he discussed with Moussa bilateral relations, the
Mideast peace process and other issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
He said it is a good opportunity to exchange views with Moussa
on the Mideast peace at a time when the peace process is going
through a vital moment.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he was pleased to discuss with his Chinese
counterpart the issues of mutual interest, expressing conviction
that Qian's visit will give a new boost to the Sino-Egyptian ties.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also praised the Sino-Egyptian cooperation in the United
Nations Security Council on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister stressed that the Iraq-UN crisis
regarding U.N. arms inspection should be solved "through peaceful
means instead of the threat of force," referring to the
U.S. warning of war.
</P>
<P>
Qian, in his turn, said that China upholds the implementation
of the relevant U.N. resolutions on the Gulf problem and arms
inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"However, the inspection, which has been going on for a long
time, should not continue indefinitely," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian also expressed his support to the UN-Iraq oil-for-food
deal which he said will contribute to relieving the sufferings of
the Iraqi people. He voiced the hope that the seven-year-old
sanctions imposed on Iraq will be gradually removed.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the last leg of Qian's Mideast tour that started on
December 19. He is scheduled to meet with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and Arab League
Secretary General Abdel Esmat Meguid Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
